const questionsData = {
  maths: { levels: [
    { level:0, topic:"Number Basics", questions:[
      { id:"m0_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Which of these numbers is prime?", options:["9","15","17","21"], answer:"17", hint:"A prime has exactly two factors: 1 and itself. Check each: 9=3×3, 15=3×5, 21=3×7, but 17 has no factors other than 1 and 17." },
      { id:"m0_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is 6 × 7?", options:["36","42","48","54"], answer:"42", hint:"Count up in 7s: 7, 14, 21, 28, 35, 42." },
      { id:"m0_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"List all the factors of 24.", answer:"The factors of 24 are: 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 8, 12, 24.", keywords:["1","2","3","4","6","8","12","24"], hint:"Work in factor pairs: 1×24, 2×12, 3×8, 4×6. That gives you 8 factors." },
      { id:"m0_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Write 60 as a product of its prime factors.", answer:"60 = 2² × 3 × 5", keywords:["2","3","5","prime"], hint:"Use a factor tree. 60 → 2×30 → 2×2×15 → 2×2×3×5. Then write using indices." },
      { id:"m0_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Explain what HCF and LCM mean. Find the HCF and LCM of 12 and 18, showing all working.", answer:"HCF = 6, LCM = 36", modelAnswer:"HCF (Highest Common Factor) is the largest number that divides into both numbers exactly.\nLCM (Lowest Common Multiple) is the smallest number that both numbers divide into exactly.\n\n12 = 2² × 3\n18 = 2 × 3²\n\nHCF = product of shared prime factors at lowest powers = 2¹ × 3¹ = 6\nLCM = product of all prime factors at highest powers = 2² × 3² = 4 × 9 = 36\n\nCheck: 6 divides into 12 ✓ and 18 ✓. Both 12 and 18 divide into 36 ✓.", hint:"Find the prime factor form of each number first. HCF uses shared factors (lowest powers). LCM uses all factors (highest powers)." }
    ]},
    { level:1, topic:"Place Value & Decimals", questions:[
      { id:"m1_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is the value of the digit 6 in 3.64?", options:["6","0.6","0.06","60"], answer:"0.6", hint:"The first digit after the decimal point is in the tenths column." },
      { id:"m1_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Round 7.654 to 2 decimal places.", options:["7.65","7.66","7.6","7.7"], answer:"7.65", hint:"Look at the third decimal place (4). Since 4 < 5, round down — the second decimal place stays as 5." },
      { id:"m1_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Write these in order from smallest to largest: 0.3, 0.03, 0.303, 0.33", answer:"0.03, 0.3, 0.303, 0.33", keywords:["0.03","0.3","0.303","0.33"], hint:"Write each with 3 decimal places: 0.030, 0.300, 0.303, 0.330. Now compare digit by digit." },
      { id:"m1_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Calculate 3.7 × 0.4, showing your method.", answer:"3.7 × 0.4 = 1.48", keywords:["1.48"], hint:"Calculate 37 × 4 = 148, then count decimal places (2 total), so answer is 1.48." },
      { id:"m1_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Explain the rules for multiplying and dividing decimals by 10, 100 and 1000. Give one example of each.", answer:"Multiplying moves digits left (decimal right); dividing moves digits right (decimal left) — 1, 2 or 3 places.", modelAnswer:"When multiplying by 10, 100 or 1000, each digit moves left on the place value grid (equivalently, the decimal point moves right):\n• 3.46 × 10 = 34.6 (1 place right)\n• 3.46 × 100 = 346 (2 places right)\n• 3.46 × 1000 = 3460 (3 places right)\n\nWhen dividing by 10, 100 or 1000, each digit moves right:\n• 52 ÷ 10 = 5.2 (1 place left)\n• 52 ÷ 100 = 0.52 (2 places left)\n• 52 ÷ 1000 = 0.052 (3 places left)\n\nCommon mistake: saying 'add a zero' — this only works for whole numbers, not decimals.", hint:"Think of digits moving on a place value grid. ×10 shifts every digit one place to the left. ÷10 shifts one place to the right." }
    ]},
    { level:2, topic:"Fractions & Percentages", questions:[
      { id:"m2_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Simplify the fraction 18/24.", options:["2/3","3/4","5/8","9/12"], answer:"3/4", hint:"Find the HCF of 18 and 24. HCF = 6. Divide both by 6: 18÷6=3, 24÷6=4." },
      { id:"m2_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is 15% of 80?", options:["10","12","15","16"], answer:"12", hint:"Find 10% first (=8), then 5% (=4). Add them: 8+4=12." },
      { id:"m2_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Convert 0.65 to a fraction in its simplest form.", answer:"13/20", keywords:["13/20","13","20"], hint:"0.65 = 65/100. Find HCF of 65 and 100 (= 5). Divide both by 5." },
      { id:"m2_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Increase £240 by 35%. Show your working.", answer:"£240 × 1.35 = £324", keywords:["324","£324","1.35"], hint:"Multiplier method: 35% increase → multiply by 1.35. Or find 35% of 240 and add it on." },
      { id:"m2_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Explain how to convert between fractions, decimals and percentages. Give a worked example of each conversion.", answer:"Fraction to decimal: divide numerator by denominator. Decimal to percentage: multiply by 100. Percentage to fraction: write over 100 and simplify.", modelAnswer:"Fraction → Decimal: divide the numerator by the denominator. E.g. 3/8 = 3 ÷ 8 = 0.375\n\nDecimal → Percentage: multiply by 100. E.g. 0.375 × 100 = 37.5%\n\nPercentage → Fraction: write over 100 and simplify. E.g. 37.5% = 37.5/100 = 75/200 = 3/8\n\nFraction → Percentage: divide then multiply by 100. E.g. 3/8 = 0.375 = 37.5%\n\nKey: these three forms all represent the same value — just written differently.", hint:"Remember the chain: fraction ÷ gives decimal, decimal ×100 gives percentage. Work through each step methodically." }
    ]},
    { level:3, topic:"Algebra Foundations", questions:[
      { id:"m3_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Simplify 3x + 2y − x + 4y.", options:["2x+6y","4x+6y","2x+2y","4x+2y"], answer:"2x+6y", hint:"Collect like terms: x terms (3x − x = 2x) and y terms (2y + 4y = 6y) separately." },
      { id:"m3_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Solve 4x − 3 = 13.", options:["x=3","x=4","x=5","x=6"], answer:"x=4", hint:"Add 3 to both sides: 4x = 16. Then divide both sides by 4." },
      { id:"m3_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Expand and simplify 3(2x + 4) − 2(x − 1).", answer:"4x + 14", keywords:["4x","14","4x+14"], hint:"Expand each bracket: 6x + 12 − 2x + 2. Watch the sign: −2 × −1 = +2. Then collect like terms." },
      { id:"m3_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Factorise fully: 6x² + 9x.", answer:"3x(2x + 3)", keywords:["3x","2x+3","3x(2x+3)"], hint:"Find the HCF of 6x² and 9x. HCF = 3x. Take 3x outside the bracket." },
      { id:"m3_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"A rectangle has length (2x + 5) cm and width (x + 3) cm. Write an expression for the perimeter and the area. If x = 4, find both values.", answer:"Perimeter = 6x+16, Area = 2x²+11x+15. When x=4: P=40cm, A=87cm²", modelAnswer:"Perimeter = 2(length + width) = 2[(2x+5)+(x+3)] = 2[3x+8] = 6x+16\n\nArea = length × width = (2x+5)(x+3)\n= 2x²+6x+5x+15 = 2x²+11x+15\n\nWhen x = 4:\nPerimeter = 6(4)+16 = 24+16 = 40 cm\nArea = 2(16)+11(4)+15 = 32+44+15 = 91 cm²\n\nCheck: length = 13cm, width = 7cm. P = 2(13+7) = 40 ✓. A = 13×7 = 91 ✓.", hint:"For perimeter use P=2(l+w). For area expand the brackets using FOIL. Always substitute x at the end." }
    ]},
    { level:4, topic:"Geometry & Shapes", questions:[
      { id:"m4_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is the sum of interior angles in a triangle?", options:["90°","180°","270°","360°"], answer:"180°", hint:"All triangles — equilateral, isosceles, scalene, right-angled — always have angles summing to 180°." },
      { id:"m4_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"A circle has radius 5 cm. What is its area? (Use π = 3.14)", options:["15.7 cm²","31.4 cm²","78.5 cm²","157 cm²"], answer:"78.5 cm²", hint:"Area = πr². r² = 25. 3.14 × 25 = 78.5." },
      { id:"m4_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Find the area and perimeter of a rectangle 8 cm × 5 cm.", answer:"Area = 40 cm², Perimeter = 26 cm", keywords:["40","26","area","perimeter"], hint:"Area = length × width. Perimeter = 2(length + width). Show both calculations clearly." },
      { id:"m4_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Calculate the volume of a cuboid with dimensions 4 cm × 3 cm × 5 cm.", answer:"Volume = 60 cm³", keywords:["60","volume","cm³"], hint:"Volume = length × width × height = 4 × 3 × 5." },
      { id:"m4_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"State Pythagoras' theorem. Use it to find: (a) the hypotenuse of a right triangle with legs 6 cm and 8 cm, (b) the missing leg when hypotenuse = 13 cm and one leg = 5 cm.", answer:"(a) 10 cm (b) 12 cm", modelAnswer:"Pythagoras' theorem: a² + b² = c², where c is the hypotenuse (longest side).\n\n(a) c² = 6² + 8² = 36 + 64 = 100\nc = √100 = 10 cm\n\n(b) 13² = 5² + b²\n169 = 25 + b²\nb² = 144\nb = √144 = 12 cm\n\nAlways check: is the hypotenuse the longest side? 10 > 8 ✓, 13 > 12 ✓.", hint:"Pythagoras: a²+b²=c² for right-angled triangles. For the hypotenuse, add the squares. For a leg, subtract. Always square root at the end." }
    ]},
    { level:5, topic:"Statistics & Probability", questions:[
      { id:"m5_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is the median of: 3, 7, 2, 9, 4?", options:["4","5","6","7"], answer:"4", hint:"First order the data: 2, 3, 4, 7, 9. The middle value (3rd of 5) is 4." },
      { id:"m5_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"A bag has 3 red balls and 5 blue balls. What is P(red)?", options:["3/8","5/8","3/5","1/2"], answer:"3/8", hint:"P(red) = number of red ÷ total. Total = 3+5=8. P(red) = 3/8." },
      { id:"m5_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Find the mean, median and mode of: 5, 3, 8, 3, 7, 6.", answer:"Mean = 32/6 ≈ 5.33, Median = 5.5, Mode = 3", keywords:["mean","median","mode","5.33","5.5","3"], hint:"Mean: add all and divide by 6. Median: order them (3,3,5,6,7,8) and find middle — average of 3rd and 4th values. Mode: most frequent." },
      { id:"m5_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"A fair spinner has sections numbered 1, 2, 3, 4. Find P(even number) and P(number greater than 2).", answer:"P(even) = 1/2, P(>2) = 1/2", keywords:["1/2","probability","even","0.5"], hint:"Even numbers: 2 and 4 (2 out of 4). Greater than 2: 3 and 4 (2 out of 4). Both give 2/4 = 1/2." },
      { id:"m5_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Explain what a frequency table is and how to use one to find the mean. A survey of shoe sizes gave: Size 5 (freq 3), Size 6 (freq 7), Size 7 (freq 5), Size 8 (freq 5). Find the mean shoe size.", answer:"Mean = (15+42+35+40)/20 = 132/20 = 6.6", modelAnswer:"A frequency table records how often each value occurs, making it easier to organise and analyse data.\n\nTo find the mean from a frequency table:\n1. Add a 'value × frequency' column\n2. Sum all frequencies (total n)\n3. Sum all (value × frequency)\n4. Mean = Σ(value × frequency) ÷ Σfrequency\n\nShoe size | Frequency | Size × Freq\n5         | 3         | 15\n6         | 7         | 42\n7         | 5         | 35\n8         | 5         | 40\nTotal     | 20        | 132\n\nMean = 132 ÷ 20 = 6.6", hint:"Add a third column: value × frequency. Sum that column and divide by total frequency. Don't just average the sizes." }
    ]},
    { level:6, topic:"Linear Graphs & Equations", questions:[
      { id:"m6_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is the gradient of the line y = 4x − 7?", options:["-7","4","7","-4"], answer:"4", hint:"In y = mx + c, m is the gradient and c is the y-intercept. Here m = 4." },
      { id:"m6_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Which of these points lies on the line y = 2x + 3?", options:["(1, 4)","(1, 5)","(2, 5)","(2, 8)"], answer:"(1, 5)", hint:"Substitute x=1: y = 2(1)+3 = 5. So (1,5) lies on the line." },
      { id:"m6_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Find the equation of the line with gradient 3 that passes through (0, −2).", answer:"y = 3x − 2", keywords:["y=3x-2","3x","-2","gradient"], hint:"Use y = mx + c. Gradient m = 3. The line passes through (0,−2) so c = −2. Write: y = 3x − 2." },
      { id:"m6_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Find the coordinates where y = 2x + 1 and y = x + 4 intersect.", answer:"x = 3, y = 7, so the point is (3, 7)", keywords:["x=3","y=7","3","7"], hint:"Set the equations equal: 2x+1 = x+4. Solve for x, then substitute back to find y." },
      { id:"m6_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Explain how to find the gradient of a straight line given two points, and how to write its equation. Use the points A(1, 3) and B(4, 9) as an example.", answer:"Gradient = (9-3)/(4-1) = 2. Equation: y = 2x + 1.", modelAnswer:"Step 1 — Find the gradient:\ngradient m = (y₂ − y₁) / (x₂ − x₁)\nUsing A(1,3) and B(4,9): m = (9−3)/(4−1) = 6/3 = 2\n\nStep 2 — Find the y-intercept:\nUse y = mx + c with point A(1,3): 3 = 2(1) + c → c = 1\n\nStep 3 — Write the equation:\ny = 2x + 1\n\nCheck with B(4,9): y = 2(4)+1 = 9 ✓\n\nThe gradient tells us: for every 1 unit right, the line rises 2 units.", hint:"Gradient = rise ÷ run = (y₂−y₁)/(x₂−x₁). Then substitute one point into y=mx+c to find c." }
    ]},
    { level:7, topic:"Quadratics & Polynomials", questions:[
      { id:"m7_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Factorise x² + 5x + 6.", options:["(x+2)(x+3)","(x+1)(x+6)","(x+2)(x+4)","(x−2)(x−3)"], answer:"(x+2)(x+3)", hint:"Find two numbers that multiply to 6 and add to 5. Answer: 2 and 3." },
      { id:"m7_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What are the solutions of x² − 9 = 0?", options:["x=3 only","x=−3 only","x=±3","x=±9"], answer:"x=±3", hint:"x² = 9, so x = √9 = ±3. Don't forget the negative square root." },
      { id:"m7_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Expand and simplify (2x − 3)(x + 5).", answer:"2x² + 7x − 15", keywords:["2x²","7x","−15","2x²+7x-15"], hint:"Use FOIL: 2x×x=2x², 2x×5=10x, −3×x=−3x, −3×5=−15. Collect like terms: 10x−3x=7x." },
      { id:"m7_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Complete the square for x² + 6x + 2.", answer:"(x + 3)² − 7", keywords:["(x+3)²","−7","complete the square"], hint:"Halve the coefficient of x: 6÷2=3. Write (x+3)², then subtract 3² and add the constant: (x+3)²−9+2=(x+3)²−7." },
      { id:"m7_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"State the quadratic formula and use it to solve 2x² − 5x − 3 = 0. Show all working and give exact answers.", answer:"x = 3 or x = −1/2", modelAnswer:"The quadratic formula: x = (−b ± √(b²−4ac)) / 2a\n\nFor 2x²−5x−3=0: a=2, b=−5, c=−3\n\nDiscriminant: b²−4ac = (−5)²−4(2)(−3) = 25+24 = 49\n\nx = (5 ± √49) / (2×2) = (5 ± 7) / 4\n\nx = (5+7)/4 = 12/4 = 3\nor x = (5−7)/4 = −2/4 = −1/2\n\nSolutions: x = 3 or x = −½\n\nCheck x=3: 2(9)−5(3)−3 = 18−15−3 = 0 ✓", hint:"Identify a, b, c carefully — watch for negatives. Calculate the discriminant (b²−4ac) first. If it's negative, there are no real solutions." }
    ]},
    { level:8, topic:"Trigonometry", questions:[
      { id:"m8_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"In a right-angled triangle, sin θ = opposite ÷ ?", options:["adjacent","hypotenuse","base","diagonal"], answer:"hypotenuse", hint:"Remember SOHCAHTOA: Sin = Opp/Hyp." },
      { id:"m8_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"A right triangle has hypotenuse 10 cm and opposite side 6 cm. What is sin θ?", options:["0.5","0.6","0.75","0.8"], answer:"0.6", hint:"sin θ = opposite/hypotenuse = 6/10 = 0.6." },
      { id:"m8_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Find angle θ in a right triangle where tan θ = 0.75. Give your answer to 1 decimal place.", answer:"θ = tan⁻¹(0.75) = 36.9°", keywords:["36.9","tan","arctan","angle"], hint:"Use the inverse: θ = tan⁻¹(0.75). On your calculator press: shift/2nd → tan → 0.75." },
      { id:"m8_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"A ladder 5 m long leans against a wall, making an angle of 60° with the ground. How far up the wall does it reach?", answer:"Height = 5 × sin 60° = 5 × 0.866 = 4.33 m", keywords:["4.33","sin60","height","sin"], hint:"Draw the triangle. The wall height is opposite, ladder is hypotenuse. Use sin 60° = opp/hyp → opp = 5 × sin 60°." },
      { id:"m8_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Explain what SOHCAHTOA stands for and when to use each ratio. Show a fully worked example for each of the three ratios using a labelled right-angled triangle.", answer:"SOH: sin=opp/hyp; CAH: cos=adj/hyp; TOA: tan=opp/adj. Apply each when two of those three sides are involved.", modelAnswer:"SOHCAHTOA is a memory aid for the three trig ratios in a right-angled triangle:\n\nSin θ = Opposite / Hypotenuse (SOH)\nCos θ = Adjacent / Hypotenuse (CAH)\nTan θ = Opposite / Adjacent (TOA)\n\nExample 1 (SOH): hyp=10, opp=?, θ=30°\nopp = 10 × sin 30° = 10 × 0.5 = 5\n\nExample 2 (CAH): hyp=8, adj=?, θ=45°\nadj = 8 × cos 45° = 8 × 0.707 = 5.66\n\nExample 3 (TOA): opp=7, adj=4, find θ\ntan θ = 7/4 = 1.75 → θ = tan⁻¹(1.75) = 60.3°\n\nChoose the ratio that connects the two sides/angle you know with what you need to find.", hint:"Label sides as O (opposite), A (adjacent), H (hypotenuse) relative to the angle θ first. Then pick the ratio that uses the two sides you have or need." }
    ]},
    { level:9, topic:"Simultaneous Equations & Inequalities", questions:[
      { id:"m9_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Solve: 2x + y = 7 and x − y = 2.", options:["x=2, y=3","x=3, y=1","x=1, y=5","x=4, y=−1"], answer:"x=3, y=1", hint:"Add the two equations: 3x = 9, so x = 3. Substitute back: 6+y=7, y=1." },
      { id:"m9_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is the smallest integer satisfying 3x + 5 > 14?", options:["2","3","4","5"], answer:"4", hint:"Solve: 3x > 9, so x > 3. The smallest integer greater than 3 is 4." },
      { id:"m9_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Use substitution to solve: y = 2x + 1 and 3x + y = 16.", answer:"x = 3, y = 7", keywords:["x=3","y=7","substitution"], hint:"Substitute y = 2x+1 into 3x+y=16: 3x+(2x+1)=16 → 5x=15 → x=3. Then y=2(3)+1=7." },
      { id:"m9_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Use elimination to solve: 3x + 2y = 12 and x + 2y = 6.", answer:"x = 3, y = 1.5", keywords:["x=3","y=1.5","elimination"], hint:"Subtract equation 2 from equation 1: (3x+2y)−(x+2y)=12−6 → 2x=6 → x=3. Substitute to find y." },
      { id:"m9_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Compare the substitution and elimination methods for solving simultaneous equations. When is each method preferable? Demonstrate with an example pair: 2x + 3y = 13 and x − y = 1.", answer:"x = 4, y = 5/3... wait let me recalculate. 2x+3y=13, x=y+1 → 2(y+1)+3y=13 → 5y=11 → y=11/5=2.2, x=3.2", modelAnswer:"Substitution: rearrange one equation for one variable, substitute into the other. Best when one equation is already solved for a variable (e.g. y = 2x+1).\n\nElimination: add or subtract equations to cancel a variable. Best when coefficients match or can be easily matched.\n\nExample: 2x+3y=13 ... (1) and x−y=1 ... (2)\n\nSubstitution: from (2), x = y+1. Substitute into (1):\n2(y+1)+3y=13 → 2y+2+3y=13 → 5y=11 → y=2.2\nx=2.2+1=3.2\n\nCheck: 2(3.2)+3(2.2)=6.4+6.6=13 ✓ and 3.2−2.2=1 ✓", hint:"Elimination works well when x or y coefficients match. Substitution works well when one equation is simple enough to rearrange. Always check your solution in both original equations." }
    ]},
    { level:10, topic:"Higher Calculus & Proof", questions:[
      { id:"m10_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Differentiate y = 3x⁴.", options:["12x³","12x⁵","3x³","4x³"], answer:"12x³", hint:"Power rule: multiply the coefficient by the power, then reduce the power by 1. 3×4=12, x⁴ becomes x³." },
      { id:"m10_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Which is the correct start to proving 'the sum of two consecutive integers is always odd'?", options:["Let the integers be n and n+1","Let the integers be 1 and 2","Substitute n = 5","Add any two numbers"], answer:"Let the integers be n and n+1", hint:"Algebraic proof must use general expressions (like n), not specific numbers." },
      { id:"m10_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Find dy/dx for y = 5x³ − 2x² + 7x − 4.", answer:"dy/dx = 15x² − 4x + 7", keywords:["15x²","−4x","7","dy/dx"], hint:"Differentiate each term: 5x³→15x², 2x²→4x, 7x→7, constant −4→0." },
      { id:"m10_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Prove that the sum of two consecutive odd numbers is always divisible by 4.", answer:"Let odds be 2n−1 and 2n+1. Sum = 4n, which is always divisible by 4.", keywords:["2n−1","2n+1","4n","divisible","proof"], hint:"Let one odd number be 2n−1. The next consecutive odd is 2n+1. Add them and factorise." },
      { id:"m10_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Explain the concept of differentiation and how to find stationary points. Find and classify the stationary points of y = x³ − 3x² − 9x + 2.", answer:"Stationary points at x=3 (min) and x=−1 (max)", modelAnswer:"Differentiation finds the rate of change (gradient) of a function at any point. dy/dx gives the gradient.\n\nStationary points occur where dy/dx = 0 (gradient is zero — turning points).\n\nFor y = x³ − 3x² − 9x + 2:\ndy/dx = 3x² − 6x − 9\n\nSet dy/dx = 0: 3x² − 6x − 9 = 0\nx² − 2x − 3 = 0\n(x−3)(x+1) = 0\nx = 3 or x = −1\n\nClassify using second derivative: d²y/dx² = 6x − 6\nAt x=3: d²y/dx²=12 > 0 → minimum\nAt x=−1: d²y/dx²=−12 < 0 → maximum\n\ny values: at x=3: y=27−27−27+2=−25. At x=−1: y=−1−3+9+2=7", hint:"Find dy/dx, set it to zero, solve for x. Then use d²y/dx² or a sign diagram to classify each point as maximum or minimum." }
    ]}
  ]},
  english: { levels: [
    { level:0, topic:"Reading Basics", questions:[
      { id:"e0_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What does 'explicit' information mean in a text?", options:["Clearly stated in the text","Implied between the lines","Hidden in subtext","Suggested by structure"], answer:"Clearly stated in the text", hint:"Explicit = directly written. Implicit = hinted at. If you can point to the exact words, it is explicit." },
      { id:"e0_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Which language technique uses 'like' or 'as' to make a comparison?", options:["Metaphor","Simile","Personification","Alliteration"], answer:"Simile", hint:"Simile uses 'like' or 'as'. Metaphor says something IS something else (no 'like'/'as')." },
      { id:"e0_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Explain what a topic sentence is and why it is important in a paragraph.", answer:"A topic sentence introduces the main idea of a paragraph, telling the reader what it will focus on and signposting the writer's argument.", keywords:["main idea","paragraph","introduces","signpost"], hint:"Think of a topic sentence as the paragraph's headline — it sets up what follows." },
      { id:"e0_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"State two strategies for finding evidence to support a point in a reading exam.", answer:"Identify key words in the question, skim the text for related words or ideas, re-read closely around key moments, select a specific quotation that directly supports your point.", keywords:["evidence","quotation","key words","support"], hint:"Good evidence is specific — a short, precise quotation beats a long paraphrase. Always link evidence back to the point." },
      { id:"e0_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Explain the difference between explicit and implicit information in a text. Why is it important to use both types of evidence in a reading response? Use an example to illustrate.", answer:"Explicit information is stated directly; implicit information is implied. Both types strengthen a response by showing surface and deep understanding.", modelAnswer:"Explicit information is directly stated in the text — the reader does not need to interpret anything. For example: 'The man was angry' tells us explicitly how he felt.\n\nImplicit information is implied or suggested rather than stated — the reader must infer it. For example: 'He slammed the door and refused to speak' implies anger without stating it.\n\nIn a reading response, using both demonstrates two levels of understanding:\n1. You can identify what is clearly there (retrieval skill)\n2. You can interpret what is suggested (inference skill)\n\nHigher marks are awarded for inference — showing you can read between the lines — but explicit evidence grounds your argument in the text. The best responses do both: quote explicitly, then explore what is implicitly suggested.", hint:"Define each term clearly first. Use a short example sentence to illustrate each. Then explain why both matter in exam responses." }
    ]},
    { level:1, topic:"Language Techniques", questions:[
      { id:"e1_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"'The wind screamed through the trees.' Which technique is this?", options:["Simile","Alliteration","Personification","Hyperbole"], answer:"Personification", hint:"Personification gives human qualities (screaming) to a non-human thing (the wind)." },
      { id:"e1_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is alliteration?", options:["Repetition of vowel sounds","Repetition of consonant sounds at the start of nearby words","Using opposites together","Exaggeration for effect"], answer:"Repetition of consonant sounds at the start of nearby words", hint:"'Peter Piper picked' — the repeated P sound at the start of words is alliteration." },
      { id:"e1_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Identify and explain one language technique in: 'The blazing sun beat down like a furnace on the cracked earth.'", answer:"Simile — 'like a furnace' compares the sun to a furnace, suggesting extreme, oppressive and unbearable heat, making the reader feel the intensity of the conditions.", keywords:["simile","furnace","heat","comparison"], hint:"Name the technique, quote it, then explain the EFFECT on the reader — what does it make them feel or think?" },
      { id:"e1_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Explain the difference in effect between a metaphor and a simile.", answer:"A metaphor creates a stronger, more immediate identification — it states something IS something else. A simile is softer, using 'like' or 'as'. Metaphors feel more powerful and absolute; similes feel more like a comparison.", keywords:["metaphor","simile","stronger","direct","comparison","effect"], hint:"Think about what 'My heart is a stone' feels like compared to 'My heart is like a stone' — which is more intense?" },
      { id:"e1_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Analyse how a writer uses at least three language techniques to create a vivid sense of atmosphere in a description of a storm. Write your analysis as a structured response.", answer:"Discuss personification, pathetic fallacy, imagery, onomatopoeia etc. — name, quote, effect for each. Explore how they work together to build atmosphere.", modelAnswer:"A skilled writer uses a range of language techniques to immerse the reader in the atmosphere of a storm.\n\nPersonification creates menace: 'The sky growled and spat at the earth' gives the storm human aggression, making it feel like an attack rather than a natural event. The reader feels threatened.\n\nOnomatopoeia heightens sensory immersion: words like 'crackle', 'hiss' and 'roar' mirror the sounds of the storm, placing the reader inside the experience rather than at a safe distance.\n\nExtended metaphor builds sustained tension: describing the storm as 'an army advancing' throughout a passage creates a coherent picture of overwhelming, organised force, building dread progressively.\n\nTogether, these techniques create atmosphere through different senses — sound, sight and emotion — building a cumulative effect that makes the storm feel immediate and threatening.", hint:"For each technique: name it, embed a quotation, explain the effect on the reader. Use precise vocabulary. Aim to show techniques working together, not just in isolation." }
    ]},
    { level:2, topic:"Structure & Form", questions:[
      { id:"e2_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What does a new paragraph in a text typically signal?", options:["The text is ending","A change in time, place, topic or speaker","A punctuation error","The start of a new chapter"], answer:"A change in time, place, topic or speaker", hint:"TIPTOP: Time, Idea, Place, Topic, or Person/speaker change — all signal a new paragraph." },
      { id:"e2_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is 'in medias res'?", options:["Starting at the very beginning","Starting in the middle of the action","Using a flashback","A circular structure"], answer:"Starting in the middle of the action", hint:"Latin for 'in the middle of things' — the story begins with action already underway, drawing the reader in immediately." },
      { id:"e2_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Explain how a writer can use sentence length for effect in a piece of writing.", answer:"Short sentences create pace, tension and emphasis. Long sentences slow the reader, building detail, complexity or a sense of breathlessness. Variation between the two creates rhythm and controls the reader's experience.", keywords:["short","tension","pace","long","complexity","rhythm"], hint:"Think about what it FEELS like to read a short sentence versus a long, winding one." },
      { id:"e2_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"What is a cyclical (circular) structure, and what effect does it create?", answer:"A circular structure ends where it began — returning to the same image, place or situation. It creates a sense of completeness, inevitability, or entrapment — suggesting nothing has changed, or that events are doomed to repeat.", keywords:["circular","cyclical","completeness","inevitability","trapped"], hint:"Think of it as the text forming a loop. What does that suggest about the character or theme?" },
      { id:"e2_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Explain how a writer uses structure to control the reader's experience of a text. Discuss at least three structural techniques in your answer.", answer:"Discuss: order of revelation, sentence/paragraph length, flashback/flash-forward, climax positioning, openings and endings. Show how structure shapes how and when the reader learns things.", modelAnswer:"Structure is the way a writer organises and arranges a text to shape the reader's experience over time.\n\nOrder of revelation controls what we know and when. A writer who withholds key information creates mystery and suspense — the reader fills gaps with inference. Revealing a twist late in a text can reframe everything that came before.\n\nSentence and paragraph length controls pace. Short paragraphs — even single sentences — create drama and emphasis. Longer, more complex paragraphs slow the reader and build density of detail.\n\nFlashback disrupts linear time, often to reveal backstory that explains present events. It creates depth of character and can shift the reader's sympathy or understanding.\n\nA shift in focus (from wide to close, from action to reflection) creates turning points. The positioning of a climax — whether early, late or mid-text — determines whether the rest of the text is build-up, aftermath, or both.\n\nStructural choices are always purposeful — every decision about order, length and focus shapes how the reader feels at each moment.", hint:"Think: what does the reader know at the START? What do they know at the END? How does the writer control that journey? That's structure." }
    ]},
    { level:3, topic:"Character & Theme", questions:[
      { id:"e3_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is a protagonist?", options:["The villain","The main character","A minor supporting character","The narrator"], answer:"The main character", hint:"Protagonist = the main character the story follows. Antagonist = the opposing force." },
      { id:"e3_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Which best describes a theme in a literary text?", options:["A summary of the plot","A central idea or message explored throughout the text","The name of the main character","The physical setting"], answer:"A central idea or message explored throughout the text", hint:"Themes are ideas — like love, power, identity, conflict. They run through the whole text, not just one scene." },
      { id:"e3_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Explain how a writer can reveal character through dialogue. Give two different techniques.", answer:"Dialogue reveals character through: word choice (formal/informal language suggesting class or education), what a character says and what they withhold, tone (aggressive, gentle, sarcastic), and how others respond to them.", keywords:["dialogue","word choice","tone","character","personality"], hint:"Think beyond just the words — consider WHO speaks, HOW they speak, and HOW MUCH they say." },
      { id:"e3_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Identify two ways a writer develops a theme throughout a text.", answer:"Through recurring symbols or motifs, through character development (how characters' journeys embody the theme), through contrasting characters who represent different aspects of the theme, or through explicit narrative comment.", keywords:["symbol","motif","recurring","character","contrast","theme"], hint:"A theme is not stated once — it is built up. What keeps coming back? What do the characters' choices say about that idea?" },
      { id:"e3_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Explore how a writer presents the theme of conflict in a literary text. You should write about: the types of conflict shown, how the writer uses language and structure to present conflict, and what the conflict reveals about characters or ideas.", answer:"Discuss: internal vs external conflict, language that conveys tension, structural moments of conflict, what conflict reveals (character, theme, society).", modelAnswer:"Conflict in literature operates on multiple levels, and skilled writers use it to reveal character, drive plot and explore ideas.\n\nExternal conflict (character vs character, or character vs society) is often shown through dialogue and action. Tense, clipped exchanges — short sentences, interruptions, loaded silences — create the sense of opposing forces. The writer may use violent or aggressive imagery to show conflict erupting into physical or social confrontation.\n\nInternal conflict (a character's struggle within themselves) is often revealed through interior monologue, contrasting emotions, or contradictory actions. A character who says one thing and does another is in internal conflict — the writer uses this gap to show psychological depth.\n\nStructurally, writers often build to a moment of peak conflict — a climax that has been carefully prepared. The aftermath of conflict — whether resolution, loss or ongoing tension — often carries the theme's meaning.\n\nUltimately, the theme of conflict often asks: what do people fight for? What does the conflict reveal about power, values, or identity?", hint:"Separate external (between characters/forces) and internal (within a character) conflict. Analyse both language AND structure — where is the moment of highest tension placed?" }
    ]},
    { level:4, topic:"Poetry Analysis", questions:[
      { id:"e4_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is a sonnet?", options:["A 14-line poem usually in iambic pentameter","A poem with no fixed form","A poem always about nature","A poem with a repeated refrain"], answer:"A 14-line poem usually in iambic pentameter", hint:"Sonnets have a fixed form: 14 lines, traditionally iambic pentameter (10 syllables per line, alternating stressed/unstressed)." },
      { id:"e4_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is enjambment?", options:["When a sentence ends at the end of a line","When a sentence runs over to the next line without a pause","Repetition of a word at the start of lines","A pause mid-line"], answer:"When a sentence runs over to the next line without a pause", hint:"Enjambment = the sentence continues onto the next line without a full stop or comma at the end of the line." },
      { id:"e4_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Explain how a poet can use imagery to convey emotion.", answer:"Imagery creates vivid mental pictures that communicate emotion indirectly. Visual imagery (light/dark) can suggest hope or despair. Tactile imagery (cold, sharp) can convey pain or fear. The reader experiences the emotion through the picture, making it more powerful than a direct statement.", keywords:["imagery","vivid","emotion","visual","convey"], hint:"Imagery works by making the reader SEE or FEEL — not just understand. Explain how the image creates an emotional response." },
      { id:"e4_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"What is a volta in a poem, and what effect does it create?", answer:"A volta is a turn or shift — in argument, mood or perspective — usually signalled by a conjunction like 'but' or 'yet', or a new stanza. It creates contrast, surprise or resolution, changing the poem's direction at a key moment and often revealing the poem's real subject or conclusion.", keywords:["volta","turn","shift","contrast","mood","resolution"], hint:"Where does the poem 'change gear'? The volta often occurs at the beginning of the final stanza or couplet in a sonnet." },
      { id:"e4_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Compare how two poems use form and structure to convey meaning. You might consider: stanza length, rhyme scheme, enjambment, rhythm and the effect of these choices.", answer:"Discuss how form mirrors content — rigid form for control, free verse for chaos, enjambment for urgency, regular rhyme for inevitability.", modelAnswer:"Poets choose form deliberately — the shape of a poem on the page and its sound are never accidental.\n\nA poem with a rigid, regular rhyme scheme (ABAB or ABBA) and consistent metre creates a sense of order and control. This can mirror a speaker who is in command of their emotions, or — ironically — suggest false control masking turmoil beneath.\n\nFree verse (no fixed rhyme or metre) can suggest freedom, chaos, or the natural rhythms of thought and speech. It is often used for confessional or emotionally raw poetry.\n\nEnjambment drives pace and can mimic urgency, anxiety, or a thought that cannot be contained. When a poet uses it unexpectedly, it can create surprise — especially if the line break falls at a crucial word.\n\nStanza breaks act like paragraph breaks — they can signal a shift in time, tone or perspective. A short, isolated stanza (even a single line) commands attention and emphasis.\n\nA strong comparative response would identify specific formal choices in each poem, explain the effect of each, and explore whether the poets' choices reinforce or contrast each other.", hint:"Don't just list techniques — explain WHY the poet made each formal choice and WHAT it communicates about the poem's meaning." }
    ]},
    { level:5, topic:"Non-Fiction & Writing", questions:[
      { id:"e5_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Which of these is a persuasive technique?", options:["Rhetorical question","Onomatopoeia","Flashback","Assonance"], answer:"Rhetorical question", hint:"A rhetorical question engages the reader by implying an answer without expecting one — it's a persuasive device. The others are more literary/poetic." },
      { id:"e5_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is the main purpose of including a counter-argument in persuasive writing?", options:["To confuse the reader","To show you understand opposing views before dismissing them","To end the argument","To provide evidence"], answer:"To show you understand opposing views before dismissing them", hint:"Acknowledging and then refuting a counter-argument (concession + rebuttal) makes your argument stronger and more credible." },
      { id:"e5_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Identify three features of a newspaper report.", answer:"Headline (grabs attention), byline (author name), lead paragraph (who/what/where/when/why), inverted pyramid structure (most important first), quotes from sources, subheadings.", keywords:["headline","lead paragraph","quotes","byline","subheading"], hint:"Think about what you see when you open a newspaper: what appears first? What is the shape of the information?" },
      { id:"e5_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Explain the effect of using the second person ('you') in persuasive writing.", answer:"Direct address ('you') involves the reader personally, making the argument feel directly relevant to them. It creates a sense of conversation and intimacy, breaking down the barrier between writer and reader and making the reader feel implicated in the issue.", keywords:["direct","address","involve","reader","personal","you"], hint:"Why does an advert say 'YOU deserve this'? Because it makes it feel personal. Same principle in persuasive essays." },
      { id:"e5_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Write a persuasive speech arguing that schools should start later in the morning. Use a range of persuasive techniques and structure your response clearly.", answer:"Use: rhetorical questions, statistics (real or implied), direct address, rule of three, anecdote, emotive language, counter-argument and rebuttal.", modelAnswer:"Good morning. I want to ask you a simple question: would YOU perform better if you were actually awake?\n\nScientific research is clear — teenagers' natural sleep cycles mean their brains are not fully functional before 9am. Yet we drag students into classrooms at 8am and wonder why they struggle. We are asking young people to learn in conditions deliberately set up against them.\n\nConsider the impact: tired students cannot concentrate, retain information or regulate their emotions. Teachers face classrooms of exhausted young people. And yet — the solution is so simple, so obvious, that it is almost painful that we have not acted.\n\nSome will argue that a later start creates problems for working parents. I understand that concern. But parents' schedules can be adapted; a teenager's developing brain cannot be rewired by willpower. We would not ask a student with a broken leg to run a race. Why do we ask students running on empty to think at full capacity?\n\nStart school later. The evidence is there. The will just needs to follow.", hint:"Open with impact (a question, bold statement or anecdote). Use short paragraphs for rhythm. Address counter-arguments directly. End with a strong call to action." }
    ]},
    { level:6, topic:"Context & Writer's Craft", questions:[
      { id:"e6_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What does 'context' mean when discussing a literary text?", options:["The exact words used","The historical, social or cultural background that influences the text","A plot summary","The physical setting"], answer:"The historical, social or cultural background that influences the text", hint:"Context is the world AROUND the text — who wrote it, when, why, for whom, and what events shaped it." },
      { id:"e6_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is pathetic fallacy?", options:["Comparing two unlike things","Using weather or environment to reflect a character's mood or the atmosphere","Exaggeration for comic effect","Describing things that cannot feel as if they can"], answer:"Using weather or environment to reflect a character's mood or the atmosphere", hint:"Pathetic fallacy = when nature mirrors emotion. A storm during a tragedy; sunshine at a joyful moment." },
      { id:"e6_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Explain how historical context can affect our understanding of a literary text.", answer:"Historical context shapes what the writer could say, what audiences expected, and what events or attitudes influenced themes. For example, wartime poetry reflects attitudes to conflict and patriotism shaped by the specific experience of that war — a modern reader must understand that context to fully appreciate the poem's meaning and power.", keywords:["historical","context","meaning","attitudes","influences","shapes"], hint:"Ask: what was happening when this was written? How does that change what the text means or what the writer's choices tell us?" },
      { id:"e6_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"What is the 'authorial voice' and how is it different from the narrator's voice?", answer:"The authorial voice is the implied perspective and values of the writer — the sense of a real person behind the text making choices. The narrator is the constructed voice telling the story, who may be unreliable, limited, or deliberately different from the author's own views.", keywords:["authorial voice","author","perspective","narrator","constructed","different"], hint:"The author creates the narrator — they are not the same. An unreliable narrator tells us something about the author's intentions precisely because they are unreliable." },
      { id:"e6_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Explore how a writer's social or historical context shapes the presentation of a key theme in a literary text you have studied.", answer:"Analyse how the period, society or biography of the writer explains their choices — use specific examples from the text to show context informing theme.", modelAnswer:"Understanding context allows us to see a literary text not just as a story but as a cultural document — a response to the world in which it was written.\n\nFor example, Victorian literature often explores themes of class, morality and social respectability because Victorian society was acutely class-conscious and governed by strict social codes. A writer like Dickens — who experienced poverty firsthand — uses theme of social injustice to critique a society that celebrated wealth while ignoring its human cost. The context of industrialisation and workhouses directly shapes characters, settings and events.\n\nA reader aware of this context can see beyond plot: Dickens' exaggerated villains are not just bad people but representatives of systems and ideologies. His language — often satirical, sometimes sentimental — reflects the tension between social critique and the need to appeal to middle-class readers who might otherwise be defensive.\n\nWithout context, a modern reader might miss the layers of irony, the cultural references, and the radical nature of what is actually being said. Context is not background decoration — it is the lens through which every word was chosen.", hint:"Pick one specific contextual fact (a historical event, social attitude, biographical detail) and trace its influence through the text with specific examples." }
    ]},
    { level:7, topic:"Comparison & Critical Analysis", questions:[
      { id:"e7_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"When comparing two texts in an exam, what should the focus always be?", options:["Which text is longer","How writers use methods to achieve specific effects","Which text was written first","Which text has more characters"], answer:"How writers use methods to achieve specific effects", hint:"Comparison is always about HOW and WHY — methods, effects, purposes. Never just WHAT happens." },
      { id:"e7_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What does 'critical analysis' mean in English?", options:["Criticising the author personally","Examining how and why a text works — its effects, methods and purposes","Summarising the plot in detail","Listing quotations without explanation"], answer:"Examining how and why a text works — its effects, methods and purposes", hint:"Critical does not mean negative. It means looking carefully and making judgements about how a text achieves its effects." },
      { id:"e7_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Describe an effective method for structuring a paragraph that compares two texts.", answer:"A comparison paragraph might use a 'point, evidence from Text 1, evidence from Text 2, analysis of similarities/differences' structure. Connectives like 'whereas', 'however', 'similarly', and 'both writers' signal comparison explicitly.", keywords:["PEEL","however","whereas","comparison","evidence","both"], hint:"The key is making the connection between texts EXPLICIT — don't write about each text separately and hope the comparison is implied." },
      { id:"e7_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"How do you evaluate the effectiveness of a writer's method?", answer:"Explain the effect on the reader; consider whether the technique successfully achieves the writer's purpose; acknowledge that different readers might respond differently; consider whether an alternative approach would have been less or more effective.", keywords:["effect","reader","purpose","evaluate","interpret","effectiveness"], hint:"Effectiveness is a judgement. Back it up: 'This is effective because...' and 'A reader might feel... because...'." },
      { id:"e7_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Compare how two writers present a similar theme using different methods. Discuss: the choices each makes, the effects these create, and what each writer seems to want the reader to think or feel.", answer:"A full comparison analyses both texts' methods, effects and purposes — drawing explicit similarities and differences, and making a judgement about which achieves its purpose more effectively.", modelAnswer:"Both writers present the theme of [e.g. isolation], yet their methods create strikingly different effects.\n\nWriter A uses a sustained metaphor of winter throughout — the protagonist's world is consistently described in cold, stark imagery ('the frozen earth of her heart', 'bare trees reaching like broken fingers'). This cumulative imagery embeds the theme in the texture of the language itself, making isolation feel total and inescapable. The reader is never allowed to forget the character's emotional state.\n\nWriter B, by contrast, presents isolation through structural absence — characters are described arriving and leaving, conversations begin and are abandoned mid-sentence, paragraphs end abruptly. The theme is conveyed not through rich description but through what is missing. This creates a different but equally powerful effect: the reader feels the isolation by experiencing something like it themselves — the frustration of incomplete communication.\n\nBoth writers successfully convey isolation, but through opposite strategies: one through abundance (dense, metaphorical language) and one through absence (structural gaps and omissions). Which is more powerful depends on whether the reader is moved more by what they are told or by what they feel.", hint:"Don't just alternate between texts — make genuine comparisons. 'Both... however... whereas... similarly...' should appear naturally in your writing." }
    ]},
    { level:8, topic:"Spoken Language & Media", questions:[
      { id:"e8_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Which of these is a typical feature of spoken language?", options:["Perfect grammar throughout","Fillers and hedges like 'um', 'you know', 'sort of'","Formal vocabulary only","Punctuation marks"], answer:"Fillers and hedges like 'um', 'you know', 'sort of'", hint:"Spoken language is spontaneous and unedited — it includes hesitations, false starts and informal expressions that written language avoids." },
      { id:"e8_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What does media bias involve?", options:["Giving a completely balanced view of every issue","Promoting a particular perspective or agenda","Informing the public neutrally","Entertaining all audiences equally"], answer:"Promoting a particular perspective or agenda", hint:"Bias in media means a publication or broadcaster consistently favours one viewpoint — through word choice, story selection, and what is omitted." },
      { id:"e8_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Identify two differences between spoken and written language.", answer:"Spoken language: uses fillers/hedges ('um', 'sort of'), features interruptions and overlaps, includes incomplete sentences and non-verbal cues (tone, gesture), is more informal and spontaneous. Written language: is planned and edited, uses punctuation to organise, is usually more formal and complete.", keywords:["fillers","interruptions","planned","formal","non-verbal","informal"], hint:"Think about a conversation vs an essay. What features of conversation would be wrong in an essay — and why?" },
      { id:"e8_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"How do presentational devices in a media text influence the reader before they read a single word?", answer:"Images, headlines, colour, font size and layout all create first impressions. A bold headline shapes the angle of the story; a carefully chosen image creates emotional associations; colour can signal urgency (red) or trustworthiness (blue). These prime the reader to interpret the text in a particular way.", keywords:["images","headline","layout","colour","impression","prime"], hint:"Think about a front page. What do you notice first? What does that make you feel before you read the story?" },
      { id:"e8_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Analyse how a media text (such as a newspaper front page, advertisement or speech) uses language and presentational features to influence its audience. Discuss both what is said and how it is said.", answer:"Analyse: word choice, tone, headline, imagery, layout, colour, speaker positioning, statistics, anecdote, emotive language — all in service of a clear purpose and audience.", modelAnswer:"Media texts are constructed to achieve a specific purpose with a specific audience, and every choice — linguistic and presentational — serves that goal.\n\nIn a broadsheet newspaper, the layout signals authority: columns of dense text, a restrained use of colour, and formal headline typography communicate seriousness and reliability. The front page hierarchy — largest headline, most prominent image, main story — tells the reader what is most important before they read anything.\n\nWord choice in headlines is precise: a tabloid might use 'FURY' where a broadsheet uses 'controversy'. The connotations are different — one implies emotion, one suggests reasoned debate. The choice of word shapes how the reader frames the story.\n\nImages rarely 'just illustrate' — they are selected and cropped to create specific impressions. A politician photographed from below looks powerful; from above, vulnerable. These are editorial choices.\n\nTogether, these devices guide the reader towards a particular reading of events. A critical reader asks: whose perspective is centred here? What has been left out? Who benefits from this framing?", hint:"Analyse BOTH language (word choice, tone, techniques) AND presentation (layout, images, colour, font). Discuss how they work together to position the reader." }
    ]},
    { level:9, topic:"Extended Writing Mastery", questions:[
      { id:"e9_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"In a high-level essay, every paragraph should include:", options:["A quotation only","An embedded quotation, explanation of its effect, and a link to the question","A plot summary","A definition of a term"], answer:"An embedded quotation, explanation of its effect, and a link to the question", hint:"PEE/PEEL structure: Point, Evidence (embedded quote), Explanation of effect, Link back to question. Never just drop a quote without analysis." },
      { id:"e9_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What does the exam instruction 'evaluate' require you to do?", options:["Describe what happens in the text","Make a judgement about how effectively the writer achieves their purpose","List all the techniques you can find","Identify the main themes"], answer:"Make a judgement about how effectively the writer achieves their purpose", hint:"Evaluate = judge. How WELL does this work? Is it effective? Why or why not? Support your judgement with evidence." },
      { id:"e9_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Explain the difference between 'analyse' and 'describe' in a GCSE English response.", answer:"Describe = identify what is there (surface level). Analyse = examine HOW and WHY — what technique is used, what effect it creates, what the writer seems to intend, how a reader might respond. Analysis goes beyond what and asks how, why and to what effect.", keywords:["analyse","how","why","effect","describe","surface"], hint:"If you write 'the author uses a metaphor' — that's description. If you write 'the author uses a metaphor which suggests... creating an effect of...' — that's analysis." },
      { id:"e9_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Describe the features of a Grade 8-9 English literature response.", answer:"Close language analysis using precise technical vocabulary; multiple interpretations of key moments; links to context (historical, social, biographical); embedded quotations rather than dropped quotes; evaluation of the writer's craft and purpose; acknowledgement that readers may respond differently.", keywords:["language analysis","interpretation","context","evaluation","Grade 9","technical"], hint:"Grade 9 is about showing you can THINK, not just identify. Offer a second interpretation. Question your own reading. Show awareness of the writer making deliberate choices." },
      { id:"e9_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Evaluate how successfully a writer presents a key character in a literary text. Make a clear argument, support it with evidence, and consider alternative interpretations.", answer:"A full evaluative response makes a clear judgement, supports it with embedded quotations, analyses methods, acknowledges complexity and alternative readings, and links to context.", modelAnswer:"[Structure of a model Grade 8-9 response]\n\nOpening — clear thesis/argument: 'The writer presents [character] as both [quality A] and [quality B], creating a deliberately ambiguous figure whose complexity challenges the reader's sympathy.'\n\nParagraph 1 — first angle with evidence: close analysis of a specific quotation, technical vocabulary, effect on reader.\n\nParagraph 2 — development/alternative interpretation: 'However, a closer reading suggests...' — show you can see more than one reading.\n\nParagraph 3 — context: 'The historical context of [period] explains why the writer might have presented... A contemporary audience would have understood...'\n\nConclusion — return to thesis, evaluate: 'The writer is most successful in presenting [character] as [quality] because... though the ambiguity around [other quality] creates a richer, less comfortable portrait.'\n\nThroughout: embedded quotations, precise terminology, assured and confident analytical voice.", hint:"A great evaluative response makes an ARGUMENT (not just points). Every paragraph serves that argument. End with a clear, justified judgement." }
    ]},
    { level:10, topic:"Grade 9 Mastery", questions:[
      { id:"e10_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What distinguishes a Grade 9 response from a Grade 7?", options:["More quotations listed","Critical, evaluative analysis with nuanced interpretation and insight into writer's craft","Better handwriting","Longer paragraphs"], answer:"Critical, evaluative analysis with nuanced interpretation and insight into writer's craft", hint:"Grade 7 analyses well. Grade 9 EVALUATES — it makes judgements, shows insight, offers multiple readings, and demonstrates that the student thinks independently." },
      { id:"e10_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is a semantic field?", options:["A type of punctuation","A group of words related by a common theme that creates atmosphere or meaning","A sentence structure technique","A type of stanza"], answer:"A group of words related by a common theme that creates atmosphere or meaning", hint:"E.g. 'dark', 'shadow', 'cold', 'grey' — all belong to a semantic field of darkness/despair. Identifying it shows you see the cumulative effect of word choices." },
      { id:"e10_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Explain how to write a convincing critical interpretation of a literary text.", answer:"A convincing critical interpretation: makes a specific, arguable claim (not just a fact); supports it with precise textual evidence; explains the effect in detail; acknowledges alternative readings and explains why your interpretation is most compelling; uses technical vocabulary confidently.", keywords:["interpretation","evidence","arguable","alternative","technical","claim"], hint:"Your interpretation must be ARGUABLE — someone should be able to disagree with it. If everyone agrees, it's not an interpretation, it's a fact." },
      { id:"e10_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"How does understanding a text's genre conventions help you analyse it more deeply?", answer:"Genre conventions create a framework of reader expectations. A writer who follows conventions signals familiarity and comfort; one who subverts them creates surprise, irony or critique. Recognising when a text works within or against its genre allows deeper analysis of intention, purpose and effect.", keywords:["genre","conventions","subvert","purpose","expectations","irony"], hint:"Ask: what would you EXPECT from this type of text? Is the writer meeting that expectation or deliberately breaking it? Why might they do that?" },
      { id:"e10_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Write a Grade 9 critical essay exploring the presentation of power in a literary text. Your response should demonstrate: a clear thesis, close language analysis, contextual understanding, multiple interpretations, and evaluative judgement.", answer:"A full Grade 9 response argues a specific, nuanced thesis about power; analyses language at word and technique level; connects to context; offers at least two interpretations; evaluates the writer's success.", modelAnswer:"Power in literature is rarely absolute — the most compelling literary presentations show power as contested, conditional and corrupting.\n\nIn [text], the writer presents power as [specific thesis — e.g. 'an illusion that requires constant performance to maintain']. This is immediately established through [specific technique]: [embedded quotation]. The [technique] creates an effect of [specific effect] — the reader is made to feel [specific reader response]. This is not accidental: [writer's name] is deliberately showing that power which must be performed so conspicuously is fragile at its core.\n\nHowever, we might also read this moment as [alternative interpretation]. From this perspective, [character]'s [action/speech/behaviour] reveals not fragility but [alternative quality]. The ambiguity is productive — it prevents the reader from settling into a comfortable moral judgement.\n\nThe context of [historical/social period] illuminates both readings. [Specific contextual point] meant that [writer's name]'s contemporary audience would have recognised [specific resonance]. A modern reader, freed from that immediate context, may read the same moment as [different resonance] — both readings are valid, and the text sustains them.\n\nUltimately, the presentation of power in [text] is most successful when it refuses simplicity — the most powerful moments are those that unsettle rather than reassure.", hint:"A Grade 9 essay has a point of view. It argues. It doesn't list — it builds. Every paragraph advances the argument and adds something new to your case." }
    ]}
  ]},
  science: { levels: [
    { level:0, topic:"Science Basics", questions:[
      { id:"s0_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is the SI unit of mass?", options:["Newton","Kilogram","Metre","Second"], answer:"Kilogram", hint:"Mass is measured in kilograms (kg). Weight (a force) is measured in Newtons." },
      { id:"s0_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Which of these is a physical change?", options:["Burning wood","Melting ice","Rusting iron","Neutralisation"], answer:"Melting ice", hint:"Physical changes are reversible and no new substance is formed. Melting ice can be re-frozen. The other three are chemical changes." },
      { id:"s0_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Define the independent variable, dependent variable and control variable in a scientific experiment.", answer:"Independent variable: the one you deliberately change. Dependent variable: the one you measure to see the effect. Control variables: all other variables kept constant to make it a fair test.", keywords:["independent","dependent","control","variable","fair test"], hint:"Think: what do I CHANGE? What do I MEASURE? What do I KEEP THE SAME? One changes, one is measured, the rest are controlled." },
      { id:"s0_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"State three features that make a scientific investigation valid and reliable.", answer:"Valid: it actually measures what it is intended to measure. Reliable: results can be repeated and reproduced by other scientists. Also important: large sample size, controlled variables, calibrated equipment, multiple repeats.", keywords:["valid","reliable","repeat","controlled","sample size"], hint:"Valid = measuring the right thing. Reliable = getting the same result if you do it again. Both are needed for trustworthy science." },
      { id:"s0_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Explain the importance of using a control group in a scientific experiment. Use an example to illustrate your answer, and explain what makes a set of results reliable.", answer:"A control group provides a baseline for comparison. Without it you cannot know whether any change is due to your variable or other factors. Reliable results are repeatable and reproducible.", modelAnswer:"A control group is a group in an experiment that does NOT receive the independent variable (the thing being tested). It provides a baseline — a point of comparison.\n\nExample: Testing whether a new drug lowers blood pressure. The control group takes a placebo (a harmless dummy pill). If both groups' blood pressure drops, the drop in the experimental group cannot be attributed to the drug alone. The control group isolates the effect of the drug specifically.\n\nWithout a control group, any observed change could be due to:\n• The act of being in a study (placebo effect)\n• Natural variation over time\n• Other environmental factors\n\nReliability means results can be repeated (same experiment, same result) and reproduced (different scientist, different lab, same result). To achieve reliability:\n• Use large sample sizes\n• Repeat the experiment multiple times\n• Control all variables except the independent one\n• Use calibrated, precise equipment", hint:"Define control group first. Then explain WHY it matters — what question would you not be able to answer without one? Then describe what makes results reliable." }
    ]},
    { level:1, topic:"Cells & Biology Basics", questions:[
      { id:"s1_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Which organelle is the site of photosynthesis?", options:["Mitochondria","Ribosome","Chloroplast","Nucleus"], answer:"Chloroplast", hint:"Chloroplasts contain chlorophyll — the green pigment that absorbs light energy for photosynthesis." },
      { id:"s1_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is diffusion?", options:["Active transport against a concentration gradient","Movement of particles from high to low concentration","Cell division","Water movement only"], answer:"Movement of particles from high to low concentration", hint:"Diffusion is PASSIVE — it requires no energy. Particles spread out from where there are more of them to where there are fewer." },
      { id:"s1_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"State three differences between a plant cell and an animal cell.", answer:"Plant cells have: a cell wall (made of cellulose), chloroplasts (for photosynthesis), and a large permanent central vacuole. Animal cells have none of these. Both have nucleus, cell membrane, mitochondria, ribosomes and cytoplasm.", keywords:["cell wall","chloroplast","vacuole","plant","animal"], hint:"Think of what a plant cell has that an animal cell does NOT. Three unique plant features: cell wall, chloroplasts, large permanent vacuole." },
      { id:"s1_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Explain why mitosis is important, and describe its outcome.", answer:"Mitosis is a type of cell division that produces two genetically identical daughter cells (same number of chromosomes as the parent). It is important for growth (increasing cell number), repair of damaged tissue, and asexual reproduction.", keywords:["mitosis","identical","growth","repair","daughter cells","chromosomes"], hint:"Key word: IDENTICAL. Mitosis produces clones of the original cell. It's for growth and repair, not for making sex cells (that's meiosis)." },
      { id:"s1_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Compare and contrast the structure of plant and animal cells. Explain how the unique features of plant cells are adapted to the cell's function.", answer:"Both have nucleus, membrane, cytoplasm, mitochondria. Plants additionally have cell wall, chloroplasts and large vacuole — each adapted to specific plant functions.", modelAnswer:"Plant and animal cells share several structures:\n• Cell membrane — controls what enters and leaves\n• Nucleus — contains DNA and controls cell activity\n• Cytoplasm — where chemical reactions occur\n• Mitochondria — site of aerobic respiration (energy release)\n• Ribosomes — site of protein synthesis\n\nPlant cells additionally have:\n\n1. Cell wall (cellulose): provides rigid support, prevents the cell from bursting when it absorbs water. Allows plants to stand upright without a skeleton.\n\n2. Chloroplasts: contain chlorophyll which absorbs light energy for photosynthesis — converting CO₂ and water into glucose. Animals cannot make their own food; plants can because of this organelle.\n\n3. Large permanent vacuole: filled with cell sap, maintains turgor (rigidity) in the cell, supports the plant. When dehydrated, cells lose turgor and the plant wilts.\n\nEach unique feature directly serves a key plant function: support, food production, and water regulation.", hint:"Structure a table in your head: shared features, then plant-only features. For each plant-only feature, explain HOW it is adapted — what does it allow the plant to DO?" }
    ]},
    { level:2, topic:"Atoms & Elements", questions:[
      { id:"s2_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"How many protons does a carbon atom have?", options:["4","6","8","12"], answer:"6", hint:"Carbon's atomic number is 6 — the atomic number equals the number of protons." },
      { id:"s2_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Elements in the same GROUP of the periodic table have the same:", options:["Number of protons","Number of electrons in their outer shell","Atomic mass","Number of neutrons"], answer:"Number of electrons in their outer shell", hint:"Group number = number of outer-shell electrons. This explains why elements in the same group have similar chemical properties." },
      { id:"s2_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Describe the structure of an atom, including the location and charge of each particle.", answer:"An atom has a central nucleus containing protons (positive charge) and neutrons (no charge). Electrons (negative charge) orbit the nucleus in shells at different energy levels. The atom is mostly empty space.", keywords:["nucleus","proton","neutron","electron","shell","positive","negative"], hint:"Three particles: proton (+), neutron (0), electron (−). Two locations: nucleus (protons + neutrons) and shells (electrons)." },
      { id:"s2_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Explain the difference between an element and a compound. Give an example of each.", answer:"An element contains only one type of atom (e.g. oxygen, O₂). A compound contains two or more different elements chemically bonded together in fixed proportions (e.g. water, H₂O). Compounds have different properties from the elements they are made from.", keywords:["element","compound","bonded","atom","proportions","one type"], hint:"Element = one type of atom only. Compound = two or more DIFFERENT elements chemically joined. A mixture is different — it can be separated physically." },
      { id:"s2_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Explain how the periodic table is organised and describe two trends you would observe going across a period and two trends going down a group.", answer:"Organised by atomic number. Across a period: atomic radius decreases, ionisation energy increases. Down a group: atomic radius increases, reactivity increases (for metals) or decreases (for non-metals).", modelAnswer:"The periodic table arranges elements in order of increasing atomic number (number of protons). Elements are organised into:\n• Periods (horizontal rows) — elements in the same period have the same number of electron shells\n• Groups (vertical columns) — elements in the same group have the same number of outer-shell electrons, giving similar chemical properties\n\nTrends across a Period (e.g. Period 3, Na to Ar):\n1. Atomic radius DECREASES — more protons pull electrons closer to the nucleus despite same number of shells\n2. Ionisation energy INCREASES — greater nuclear charge makes it harder to remove an electron\n\nTrends down a Group (e.g. Group 1, Li to Cs):\n1. Atomic radius INCREASES — each element has one more electron shell than the one above\n2. Reactivity INCREASES (Group 1 metals) — outer electron is further from the nucleus and more easily lost. (Note: Group 7 non-metals become LESS reactive down the group.)", hint:"Organise your answer: first explain HOW it's arranged (atomic number, periods, groups), then give TWO trends across a period and TWO down a group. Always explain WHY the trend occurs." }
    ]},
    { level:3, topic:"Forces & Motion", questions:[
      { id:"s3_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Which statement best describes Newton's First Law of Motion?", options:["Force = mass × acceleration","An object remains at rest or moves at constant velocity unless acted on by a resultant force","Every action has an equal and opposite reaction","Work done = force × distance"], answer:"An object remains at rest or moves at constant velocity unless acted on by a resultant force", hint:"Newton's 1st Law = the law of inertia. Objects don't change their motion unless a net (resultant) force acts on them." },
      { id:"s3_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"A 4 kg object is acted on by a resultant force of 20 N. What is its acceleration?", options:["0.2 m/s²","5 m/s²","80 m/s²","16 m/s²"], answer:"5 m/s²", hint:"F = ma, so a = F/m = 20/4 = 5 m/s²." },
      { id:"s3_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Define velocity and explain how it differs from speed.", answer:"Speed is the rate of change of distance — it is a scalar quantity (magnitude only). Velocity is the rate of change of displacement — it is a vector quantity (magnitude AND direction). A car going around a roundabout at constant speed has changing velocity because direction changes.", keywords:["velocity","speed","vector","scalar","direction","displacement"], hint:"Both measure how fast. The difference is direction. Speed has no direction (scalar); velocity does (vector)." },
      { id:"s3_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"A car travels 150 m in 10 s. Calculate its speed. Then calculate the braking force needed to stop a 1200 kg car travelling at 20 m/s in 5 s.", answer:"Speed = 150/10 = 15 m/s. Deceleration = 20/5 = 4 m/s². Force = 1200 × 4 = 4800 N.", keywords:["15","4800","deceleration","F=ma","m/s"], hint:"Speed = distance/time. For force: first find deceleration (change in velocity / time), then use F = ma." },
      { id:"s3_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"State Newton's three laws of motion and explain each with a real-world example. How do these laws explain the behaviour of objects in everyday life?", answer:"1st: inertia (seatbelts). 2nd: F=ma (pushing a trolley). 3rd: action-reaction (rocket thrust).", modelAnswer:"Newton's First Law (Inertia): An object at rest stays at rest, and an object in motion stays in motion at constant velocity, unless a resultant force acts on it.\nExample: A passenger lurches forward in a braking car — their body was moving and wanted to keep moving (inertia) while the car decelerated. Seatbelts apply a force to stop them.\n\nNewton's Second Law: F = ma (Force = mass × acceleration). The greater the force, the greater the acceleration; the greater the mass, the smaller the acceleration for the same force.\nExample: Pushing a heavy loaded supermarket trolley requires more force than an empty one. Doubling the force on the same trolley doubles its acceleration.\n\nNewton's Third Law: Every action has an equal and opposite reaction force — forces always act in pairs on different objects.\nExample: A rocket expels gas downward (action); the gas pushes the rocket upward with equal force (reaction). Jumping works the same way — you push the ground down, the ground pushes you up.", hint:"For each law: state it precisely, give a real example, explain how the law applies to that example. Show understanding, not just memory." }
    ]},
    { level:4, topic:"Energy & Electricity", questions:[
      { id:"s4_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is the unit of electrical resistance?", options:["Volt (V)","Ampere (A)","Ohm (Ω)","Watt (W)"], answer:"Ohm (Ω)", hint:"Remember V = IR: Voltage (V), Current (A, Amperes), Resistance (Ω, Ohms)." },
      { id:"s4_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"In a series circuit with two bulbs, what happens if one bulb breaks?", options:["Both bulbs go out","Only that bulb goes out","The circuit continues normally","Both bulbs get brighter"], answer:"Both bulbs go out", hint:"In a series circuit there is only ONE path for current. If it is broken anywhere, current stops flowing everywhere." },
      { id:"s4_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"State Ohm's Law. A component has a voltage of 12 V across it and a current of 3 A flowing through it. Calculate its resistance.", answer:"Ohm's Law: V = IR. R = V/I = 12/3 = 4 Ω.", keywords:["V=IR","Ohm","4","resistance","Ohm's Law"], hint:"Rearrange V = IR to find R: R = V ÷ I. Make sure units are consistent." },
      { id:"s4_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Explain the difference between renewable and non-renewable energy sources. Give one example of each.", answer:"Renewable energy sources are replenished naturally and will not run out (e.g. wind, solar, hydroelectric). Non-renewable sources are finite and will eventually be exhausted (e.g. coal, oil, natural gas). Burning non-renewables releases CO₂, contributing to climate change.", keywords:["renewable","non-renewable","wind","coal","replenished","finite"], hint:"Renewable = can be replaced. Non-renewable = will run out. Wind and solar are always renewable; fossil fuels are always non-renewable." },
      { id:"s4_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Describe how energy is transferred in an electrical circuit. Explain what factors affect the resistance of a wire, and why resistance matters in circuit design.", answer:"Energy transfers from power supply to components via electrical work. Resistance depends on length, cross-sectional area, material and temperature. Higher resistance = less current for same voltage.", modelAnswer:"In an electrical circuit, energy is transferred by the movement of charge (current). The power supply (battery/mains) does work on the charges, giving them energy. As charges pass through components (bulbs, resistors, motors), they transfer energy — to light, heat, sound or kinetic energy.\n\nFactors affecting resistance of a wire:\n1. Length — longer wire = greater resistance (more collisions between electrons and ions)\n2. Cross-sectional area — thicker wire = lower resistance (more paths for electrons)\n3. Material — different metals have different resistivities (copper has low resistance; nichrome has high resistance)\n4. Temperature — for most metals, higher temperature = higher resistance (ions vibrate more, causing more collisions)\n\nResistance matters in circuit design because it controls current flow (V = IR). A higher resistance means less current for the same voltage. Designers use this to protect components (series resistors limit current), generate heat (kettle elements have high resistance), or create potential dividers to control voltage.", hint:"For energy transfer: say WHERE energy comes from (supply) and WHERE it goes (components). For resistance factors: give 4 factors and explain the physics of each." }
    ]},
    { level:5, topic:"Chemical Reactions", questions:[
      { id:"s5_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"In a chemical equation, what does the arrow (→) represent?", options:["The reactants equal the products in mass","The reactants are converted into the products","The reaction is reversible","The substances are just mixed together"], answer:"The reactants are converted into the products", hint:"Reactants (left of arrow) → Products (right of arrow). The arrow means 'react to form'. A ⇌ symbol would mean reversible." },
      { id:"s5_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Which type of reaction releases heat energy to the surroundings?", options:["Endothermic","Exothermic","Only neutralisation","Only combustion"], answer:"Exothermic", hint:"Exo = exit/outside. Exothermic reactions release energy (heat) to surroundings — temperature of surroundings increases. Hand warmers, combustion, and neutralisation are examples." },
      { id:"s5_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Balance the following equation: H₂ + O₂ → H₂O", answer:"2H₂ + O₂ → 2H₂O", keywords:["2H₂","O₂","2H₂O","balanced"], hint:"Count atoms on each side. Unbalanced: 2H and 2O left, 2H and 1O right. Add a 2 in front of H₂O, then 2 in front of H₂. Check: 4H and 2O each side." },
      { id:"s5_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Explain what happens in a neutralisation reaction and write a word equation for one example.", answer:"An acid reacts with a base (or alkali) to form a salt and water. The pH moves towards 7. Example: hydrochloric acid + sodium hydroxide → sodium chloride + water. HCl + NaOH → NaCl + H₂O.", keywords:["acid","base","salt","water","neutralisation","pH"], hint:"Acid + Base → Salt + Water. The name of the salt depends on: (1) the acid used, (2) the base used." },
      { id:"s5_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Explain the difference between exothermic and endothermic reactions, including energy profile diagrams. Then describe how you could investigate the effect of concentration on the rate of a chemical reaction.", answer:"Exothermic: energy released, products at lower energy. Endothermic: energy absorbed, products at higher energy. Rate investigation: vary concentration of acid, measure time for reaction.", modelAnswer:"Exothermic reactions release energy to surroundings — the products have less energy than the reactants. On an energy profile diagram, the products are lower than the reactants. Temperature of surroundings INCREASES. Examples: combustion, respiration, neutralisation.\n\nEndothermic reactions absorb energy from surroundings — products have MORE energy than reactants. On the diagram, products are HIGHER than reactants. Temperature of surroundings DECREASES. Examples: photosynthesis, thermal decomposition, dissolving ammonium nitrate.\n\nBoth diagrams show an activation energy 'hump' — the minimum energy needed to start the reaction.\n\nInvestigating the effect of concentration on reaction rate:\n• Method: React marble chips (CaCO₃) with hydrochloric acid at different concentrations. Measure volume of CO₂ produced per minute, or time for a cross to disappear (sodium thiosulfate method).\n• Independent variable: concentration of acid\n• Dependent variable: rate of reaction (time or volume)\n• Control variables: temperature, volume of acid, surface area of chips, mass of chips\n• Prediction: higher concentration → faster rate, because more reactant particles per unit volume → more frequent successful collisions.", hint:"Exo vs endo: remember which releases and which absorbs energy. For the investigation, use the standard framework: IV, DV, CVs, prediction with particle theory explanation." }
    ]},
    { level:6, topic:"Biology: Body Systems", questions:[
      { id:"s6_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Where does digestion begin?", options:["Stomach","Small intestine","Mouth","Oesophagus"], answer:"Mouth", hint:"Digestion begins in the mouth — physical digestion (chewing) and chemical digestion (amylase in saliva breaking down starch)." },
      { id:"s6_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is the main role of the alveoli in the lungs?", options:["Pump blood to the body","Filter dust from the air","Allow gas exchange between air and blood","Produce mucus to trap pathogens"], answer:"Allow gas exchange between air and blood", hint:"Alveoli are tiny air sacs with thin walls and rich blood supply. O₂ diffuses into blood; CO₂ diffuses out." },
      { id:"s6_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Describe the role of enzymes in digestion. Give two examples of digestive enzymes and the substrates they act on.", answer:"Enzymes are biological catalysts that speed up the breakdown of large, insoluble food molecules into small, soluble ones that can be absorbed. Amylase breaks starch into sugars (maltose). Protease breaks proteins into amino acids. Lipase breaks lipids (fats) into fatty acids and glycerol.", keywords:["enzyme","catalyst","amylase","starch","protease","amino acids","lipase"], hint:"Enzymes are specific — each works on one type of molecule (substrate). Name the enzyme AND its substrate AND the product." },
      { id:"s6_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Write the word equation for aerobic respiration and explain where in the cell it occurs.", answer:"Glucose + Oxygen → Carbon dioxide + Water (+ energy released). Aerobic respiration occurs in the mitochondria. It releases energy for all life processes.", keywords:["glucose","oxygen","carbon dioxide","water","respiration","mitochondria","energy"], hint:"Aerobic = requires oxygen. Word equation: glucose + oxygen → carbon dioxide + water. The energy released is used for movement, growth, maintaining temperature etc." },
      { id:"s6_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Describe how the circulatory system is structured and how it is adapted for the efficient transport of materials around the body.", answer:"Double circulation: pulmonary (heart→lungs→heart) and systemic (heart→body→heart). Heart as pump. Arteries, veins, capillaries adapted for their roles.", modelAnswer:"The human circulatory system is a DOUBLE CIRCULATION — blood passes through the heart twice for each complete circuit.\n\n1. Pulmonary circulation: right side of heart → lungs (to pick up O₂ and drop CO₂) → left side of heart\n2. Systemic circulation: left side of heart → body (to deliver O₂ and nutrients) → right side of heart\n\nThe heart is a muscular pump with four chambers. The left side pumps oxygenated blood at high pressure to the body; the right side pumps deoxygenated blood to the lungs at lower pressure.\n\nBlood vessels are adapted for their functions:\n• Arteries: thick, muscular walls to withstand high pressure; carry blood AWAY from heart\n• Veins: thinner walls, valves to prevent backflow; carry blood TO the heart\n• Capillaries: one-cell-thick walls for easy diffusion; huge surface area for exchange of O₂, CO₂, nutrients and waste\n\nBlood itself is adapted: red blood cells (haemoglobin for O₂ transport, no nucleus for more space), plasma (carries dissolved nutrients, CO₂, hormones, urea), platelets (clotting).", hint:"Describe the route of blood: lungs → heart → body → heart. Then describe each vessel type's structure and HOW that structure suits its function." }
    ]},
    { level:7, topic:"Waves & Light", questions:[
      { id:"s7_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is the approximate speed of light in a vacuum?", options:["3 × 10⁶ m/s","3 × 10⁸ m/s","3 × 10¹⁰ m/s","300 m/s"], answer:"3 × 10⁸ m/s", hint:"The speed of light c ≈ 3 × 10⁸ m/s (300,000,000 m/s or 300,000 km/s). This applies to all electromagnetic waves in a vacuum." },
      { id:"s7_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Why does refraction occur when light passes from one medium to another?", options:["It is reflected at the surface","It changes speed as it enters the new medium","It diffracts around the boundary","It is absorbed at the interface"], answer:"It changes speed as it enters the new medium", hint:"Refraction = bending of waves due to a change in speed. Light slows down going from air to glass (and bends towards the normal)." },
      { id:"s7_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Define frequency, wavelength and amplitude of a wave. State the unit of each.", answer:"Frequency: number of complete waves per second; unit Hertz (Hz). Wavelength: distance between two identical points on adjacent waves (e.g. crest to crest); unit metres. Amplitude: maximum displacement from the rest position; unit metres.", keywords:["frequency","wavelength","amplitude","Hz","metres","displacement"], hint:"Frequency = waves per second. Wavelength = length of one wave. Amplitude = height of the wave. v = fλ links them all." },
      { id:"s7_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"State the law of reflection and explain how it applies to a plane mirror.", answer:"Law of reflection: the angle of incidence equals the angle of reflection (both measured from the normal to the surface). In a plane mirror, light hitting the surface at 30° to the normal reflects at 30° to the normal on the other side. The image formed is virtual, upright and the same size as the object.", keywords:["angle of incidence","angle of reflection","normal","reflection","equal"], hint:"Both angles are measured from the NORMAL (a line perpendicular to the surface), not from the surface itself." },
      { id:"s7_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Compare transverse and longitudinal waves, giving an example of each. Then describe the electromagnetic spectrum, including the order of waves by frequency and two uses of any two wave types.", answer:"Transverse: vibration perpendicular to direction (e.g. light). Longitudinal: vibration parallel (e.g. sound). EM spectrum: radio, micro, IR, visible, UV, X-ray, gamma — increasing frequency/energy.", modelAnswer:"Transverse waves: the vibration is PERPENDICULAR (at right angles) to the direction of energy transfer. Example: light, water waves, all electromagnetic waves. You can see the oscillation as a sideways wave.\n\nLongitudinal waves: the vibration is PARALLEL to the direction of energy transfer. Example: sound waves, ultrasound, P-waves in earthquakes. The wave consists of compressions and rarefactions.\n\nKey difference: transverse waves can be polarised (vibrations in one plane); longitudinal waves cannot.\n\nThe Electromagnetic Spectrum (in order of increasing frequency / decreasing wavelength):\nRadio → Microwave → Infrared → Visible → Ultraviolet → X-ray → Gamma ray\n\nAll travel at 3 × 10⁸ m/s in a vacuum.\n\nUses:\n• Microwaves: cooking food (absorbed by water molecules), satellite communications\n• X-rays: medical imaging (penetrate soft tissue but not bone), airport security scanners\n• Infrared: thermal imaging cameras, TV remote controls, optical fibres\n• Gamma rays: killing cancer cells (radiotherapy), sterilising medical equipment", hint:"For transverse vs longitudinal: the key word is the direction of vibration RELATIVE to direction of travel. For the EM spectrum, memorise the order and know one use + one hazard for each wave type." }
    ]},
    { level:8, topic:"Genetics & Evolution", questions:[
      { id:"s8_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is a gene?", options:["An entire chromosome","A section of DNA that codes for a specific protein or characteristic","A single nucleotide base pair","The organism's complete set of DNA"], answer:"A section of DNA that codes for a specific protein or characteristic", hint:"Gene → specific instruction. Chromosome → book of instructions. Genome → entire library." },
      { id:"s8_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Two carriers (Aa) of a recessive condition have children. What is the probability of a child being affected (aa)?", options:["0%","25%","50%","75%"], answer:"25%", hint:"Cross Aa × Aa: offspring ratios are AA:Aa:aa = 1:2:1. Only aa is affected = 1 in 4 = 25%." },
      { id:"s8_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Explain the difference between genotype and phenotype, and between dominant and recessive alleles.", answer:"Genotype: the alleles an organism carries (e.g. Bb). Phenotype: the observable characteristic expressed (e.g. brown eyes). Dominant alleles are expressed even when only one copy is present. Recessive alleles are only expressed when two copies are present (homozygous recessive).", keywords:["genotype","phenotype","alleles","dominant","recessive","observable"], hint:"Genotype = what you HAVE (the letters). Phenotype = what you SEE (the physical trait). Dominant masks recessive." },
      { id:"s8_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Describe how natural selection leads to evolution over many generations.", answer:"1. There is variation in a population due to mutations. 2. Individuals with advantageous traits are better adapted to survive and reproduce. 3. They pass on beneficial alleles to offspring. 4. Over many generations, the frequency of beneficial alleles increases in the population — the species evolves.", keywords:["variation","selection","survival","reproduce","alleles","population","evolution"], hint:"Key steps: VARIATION exists → SELECTION by environment → REPRODUCTION passes on traits → CHANGE in population over generations. This is Darwin's mechanism." },
      { id:"s8_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Explain how DNA carries genetic information and describe how a mutation can affect an organism. Include the relationship between DNA, genes, proteins and characteristics.", answer:"DNA → gene → mRNA → protein → characteristic. Mutations change base sequence, potentially changing amino acid sequence, changing protein shape/function.", modelAnswer:"DNA (deoxyribonucleic acid) is a double helix made of nucleotides. Each nucleotide contains a sugar, phosphate, and one of four bases (A, T, C, G). The sequence of bases along a gene carries the code for building a specific protein.\n\nDNA → Protein → Characteristic:\n1. Gene: a specific sequence of DNA bases (on a chromosome)\n2. The gene is transcribed into mRNA, which carries the code out of the nucleus\n3. Ribosomes read the mRNA and assemble amino acids into a protein\n4. The protein's structure determines its function (e.g. enzyme, structural protein, hormone)\n5. The protein produces a characteristic (e.g. eye colour, blood type)\n\nMutations are changes to the DNA base sequence. Effects depend on the change:\n• Silent mutation: new codon codes for same amino acid — no change to protein\n• Missense mutation: new codon codes for different amino acid — protein may be non-functional\n• Frameshift mutation: insertion or deletion shifts the reading frame — usually severely disrupts the protein\n\nExample: sickle cell anaemia is caused by one base change in haemoglobin gene → abnormal haemoglobin → red blood cells change shape → impaired oxygen transport.", hint:"Follow the pathway: DNA → gene → protein → characteristic. Then explain what happens when a mutation changes the DNA sequence at each step." }
    ]},
    { level:9, topic:"Earth Science & Space", questions:[
      { id:"s9_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What causes most earthquakes?", options:["Volcanic eruptions at the surface","Movement of tectonic plates at fault lines","Changes in ocean temperature","Seasonal weather patterns"], answer:"Movement of tectonic plates at fault lines", hint:"Tectonic plates move slowly. Where they meet (plate boundaries/fault lines), stress builds up and releases suddenly as seismic waves — an earthquake." },
      { id:"s9_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Which type of rock is formed from cooled magma?", options:["Sedimentary","Metamorphic","Igneous","Fossiliferous"], answer:"Igneous", hint:"Igneous = fire. Formed when magma (underground) or lava (at surface) cools and solidifies. Examples: granite (slow cooling) and basalt (fast cooling)." },
      { id:"s9_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Describe the rock cycle, explaining how each of the three main rock types can form from the others.", answer:"Igneous rock is weathered/eroded → sediment → compressed to form sedimentary rock → heated/pressurised to form metamorphic rock → melted to magma → cooled to form igneous rock. Any rock can eventually be recycled through the cycle.", keywords:["igneous","sedimentary","metamorphic","magma","erosion","cycle","weathered"], hint:"Think of a triangle: igneous → sedimentary → metamorphic → igneous. Each transition has a process: weathering/erosion, compression, heat/pressure, melting." },
      { id:"s9_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Name the four layers of the Earth from the surface inward and describe the state (solid/liquid) of each.", answer:"Crust (solid, thin), Mantle (solid but can flow slowly — plastic/semi-solid), Outer Core (liquid iron and nickel), Inner Core (solid iron and nickel under enormous pressure).", keywords:["crust","mantle","outer core","inner core","solid","liquid"], hint:"From outside to inside: Crust → Mantle → Outer Core → Inner Core. The outer core is the only liquid layer." },
      { id:"s9_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Describe the evidence that supports the theory of plate tectonics and explain what happens at two different types of plate boundary.", answer:"Evidence: continental fit (Pangaea), matching fossils, mid-ocean ridges, seafloor spreading, paleomagnetism. Boundaries: constructive (plates separate, new crust), destructive (subduction, volcanoes/earthquakes), conservative (slide past, earthquakes).", modelAnswer:"Evidence for plate tectonics:\n1. Continental fit: the coastlines of South America and Africa fit together like jigsaw pieces, suggesting they were once joined (Pangaea)\n2. Matching fossils: identical fossils of Mesosaurus found on both sides of the Atlantic — couldn't have crossed the ocean\n3. Paleomagnetism: magnetic striping symmetrically either side of mid-ocean ridges shows seafloor spreading as new crust forms\n4. Earthquake and volcano distribution: concentrated at plate boundaries, not randomly distributed\n5. Deep ocean trenches: form where plates subduct\n\nPlate Boundaries:\n\nConstructive (Divergent): plates move APART. Magma rises to fill the gap, creating new oceanic crust. Mid-ocean ridges form. Example: Mid-Atlantic Ridge. Shallow earthquakes, gentle volcanic eruptions.\n\nDestructive (Convergent — ocean meets continent): oceanic plate subducts beneath continental plate. Ocean plate melts. Magma rises, forming explosive volcanoes. Deep ocean trench forms. Example: Nazca plate beneath South American plate (creating Andes). Strong earthquakes, explosive eruptions.\n\nConservative (Transform): plates slide horizontally past each other. No crust created or destroyed. Friction causes powerful earthquakes. Example: San Andreas Fault, California.", hint:"Evidence: give 3-4 specific types and explain what each shows. For boundaries: describe what happens to the plates and what geological features/events result." }
    ]},
    { level:10, topic:"Advanced Science & Exam Mastery", questions:[
      { id:"s10_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What does Einstein's equation E = mc² tell us?", options:["Force equals mass times acceleration","Mass and energy are equivalent and interchangeable","Power equals current times voltage","Energy equals Planck's constant times frequency"], answer:"Mass and energy are equivalent and interchangeable", hint:"E = mc²: even a tiny mass (m) corresponds to an enormous amount of energy (E) because c² (speed of light squared) is huge." },
      { id:"s10_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"In science, a result is described as 'valid' when:", options:["It is exactly repeatable every time","It actually measures what it is intended to measure under fair conditions","It matches the expected theoretical result","It is very precise"], answer:"It actually measures what it is intended to measure under fair conditions", hint:"Validity is about measuring the right thing correctly. Precision and repeatability are related but different concepts." },
      { id:"s10_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Explain the difference between accuracy and precision in scientific measurement.", answer:"Accuracy: how close a measurement is to the true value. Precision: how consistent repeated measurements are with each other. A result can be precise but inaccurate (consistently wrong due to systematic error). Ideal results are both accurate AND precise.", keywords:["accuracy","precision","true value","consistent","systematic error"], hint:"Accurate = close to truth. Precise = close to each other. Think of a dartboard: all darts close together but away from bullseye = precise but not accurate." },
      { id:"s10_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Describe two practices that scientists use to ensure their findings are considered trustworthy by the scientific community.", answer:"1. Peer review: independent scientists check the method, data and conclusions before publication. Catches errors and prevents false claims. 2. Replication: other scientists repeat the experiment to check results are reproducible. Also: large sample sizes, controlled variables, blind/double-blind trials.", keywords:["peer review","replication","reproducible","independent","sample size"], hint:"Think about what happens AFTER an experiment: who checks it? Who tries to repeat it? These processes are what make science self-correcting." },
      { id:"s10_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Evaluate the evidence for human-induced climate change. In your answer: describe the evidence, explain the enhanced greenhouse effect, and discuss one way humans can reduce their carbon footprint.", answer:"Evidence: rising CO₂ from ice cores/measurements, rising global temperatures, melting ice caps, sea level rise, species range shifts. Enhanced greenhouse effect: more CO₂ traps more heat. Reduction: renewable energy, reduced deforestation.", modelAnswer:"Evidence for human-induced climate change:\n• Atmospheric CO₂ has risen from ~280 ppm (pre-industrial) to over 420 ppm (2024) — directly correlated with industrialisation and fossil fuel burning\n• Ice core data shows temperature and CO₂ levels have moved together over 800,000 years\n• Global average temperature has risen approximately 1.2°C since 1850\n• Arctic sea ice extent has decreased significantly; glaciers worldwide are retreating\n• Sea levels are rising due to thermal expansion and ice melt\n\nThe Enhanced Greenhouse Effect:\nGreenhouse gases (CO₂, CH₄, N₂O, water vapour) absorb infrared radiation re-emitted by Earth's surface, then re-emit it in all directions — warming the lower atmosphere. Human activities have increased concentrations of these gases, enhancing the natural greenhouse effect beyond its pre-industrial level, causing net warming.\n\nReducing carbon footprint — Renewable Energy:\nReplacing fossil fuel power stations with wind, solar or nuclear power eliminates CO₂ emissions from electricity generation. Advantages: zero-carbon operation, increasingly cost-competitive. Challenges: intermittency of wind/solar requires energy storage; nuclear has waste disposal issues. However, the long-term benefit — stabilising atmospheric CO₂ — outweighs the transition costs.", hint:"Structure your answer: evidence first (give specific examples), then mechanism (how CO₂ causes warming), then a specific mitigation strategy with its pros and cons." }
    ]}
  ]},
  geography: { levels: [
    { level:0, topic:"Geography Basics", questions:[
      { id:"g0_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What does GDP stand for?", options:["General Development Plan","Gross Domestic Product","Global Development Progress","Geographic Data Points"], answer:"Gross Domestic Product", hint:"GDP = the total monetary value of all goods and services produced in a country in a year. Used as a measure of economic size." },
      { id:"g0_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Which of these is a physical geographical feature?", options:["A motorway","A reservoir","A mountain range","A city"], answer:"A mountain range", hint:"Physical geography = natural features (mountains, rivers, coastlines). Human geography = features created by people (roads, cities, reservoirs)." },
      { id:"g0_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Explain the difference between physical geography and human geography. Give one example of each.", answer:"Physical geography studies natural features and processes of the Earth (e.g. rivers, volcanoes, climate). Human geography studies people, their activities and their impact on the environment (e.g. urbanisation, migration, economic development).", keywords:["physical","human","natural","settlements","climate","people"], hint:"Physical = nature. Human = people and their activities. Many geographical issues involve BOTH — this is where the subjects overlap." },
      { id:"g0_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Name the eight points of a compass in clockwise order starting from North.", answer:"North (N), North-East (NE), East (E), South-East (SE), South (S), South-West (SW), West (W), North-West (NW).", keywords:["North","South","East","West","NE","NW","SE","SW"], hint:"Start at N and go clockwise: N, NE, E, SE, S, SW, W, NW. Memory aid: Never Eat Shredded Wheat (N, E, S, W for the four main points)." },
      { id:"g0_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Explain the difference between physical and human geography, and describe a real-world geographical issue that involves both. Explain why geographers need to understand both types.", answer:"Physical: natural world (climate, landforms). Human: people and activities. Real-world issues like flooding involve both: physical causes (heavy rainfall, river processes) and human factors (land use, urban development, flood management).", modelAnswer:"Physical geography focuses on the natural world — studying processes like weathering, erosion, climate, and ecosystems that shape the Earth's surface without human involvement.\n\nHuman geography focuses on people — how they organise themselves (settlements, cities), how they move (migration), how they use resources, and how economies develop.\n\nA real-world issue requiring both: Flooding in a city like York (UK)\n• Physical factors: heavy rainfall, river discharge, impermeable geology, topography\n• Human factors: urban development increasing surface runoff, flood plain building, deforestation upstream removing interception, climate change (human-induced) intensifying rainfall events\n• Management: engineering solutions (flood barriers = physical) and planning decisions (no-build zones = human)\n\nGeographers need both lenses because real problems are never purely physical or purely human. A flood is natural, but human choices determine its impact and the response. Understanding the interaction between physical processes and human decisions is the core of geographical thinking.", hint:"Define both types clearly. Then pick ONE real example and trace both its physical AND human dimensions. Show how they interact." }
    ]},
    { level:1, topic:"Map Skills", questions:[
      { id:"g1_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"On an OS map, what does a contour line represent?", options:["A river","A road","A line joining points of equal height above sea level","A national border"], answer:"A line joining points of equal height above sea level", hint:"Contour lines = lines of equal height (elevation). They show the shape of the land without you being there." },
      { id:"g1_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"On a 1:50,000 scale map, what does 2 cm on the map represent in reality?", options:["50 m","500 m","1 km","100 km"], answer:"1 km", hint:"1:50,000 means 1 cm = 50,000 cm = 500 m. So 2 cm = 1000 m = 1 km." },
      { id:"g1_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Explain how to give a six-figure grid reference for a point on an OS map.", answer:"Read the easting (numbers along the bottom) to the left of the point, then estimate tenths across the grid square. Then read the northing (numbers up the side) below the point, and estimate tenths up. Always eastings first, then northings. Format: 3 digits for easting, 3 for northing (e.g. 456 789).", keywords:["eastings","northings","6-figure","grid reference","tenths"], hint:"'Along the corridor, then up the stairs' — eastings (horizontal) first, northings (vertical) second. Always 3 digits for each." },
      { id:"g1_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"What do closely spaced contour lines indicate? What about widely spaced contours? What does the shape of contours tell us about valleys and ridges?", answer:"Closely spaced = steep slope. Widely spaced = gentle slope. No contours = flat land. V-shapes pointing uphill = valley. V-shapes pointing downhill = ridge/spur.", keywords:["steep","gentle","slope","contour","valley","ridge","closely spaced"], hint:"Think of contour lines as layers of a cake seen from above. Close together = the sides are steep. Far apart = gently sloping." },
      { id:"g1_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Explain why geographers use different types of maps for different purposes. Describe three different map types and explain what each is best used for.", answer:"OS maps: topography and navigation. Choropleth maps: showing spatial distribution of a variable (e.g. population density). Dot maps: showing distribution of individual occurrences. Each matches the type of data and the question being investigated.", modelAnswer:"Different maps are tools designed for different questions. Choosing the right map type is a key geographical skill.\n\n1. Ordnance Survey (OS) Maps: show detailed topography — contour lines, land use, roads, settlements, symbols for features. Best used for: navigation, understanding landscape, field work planning. Scale affects level of detail (1:25,000 for walking; 1:250,000 for regional overview).\n\n2. Choropleth Maps: use shading or colour to show the intensity of a variable across areas (e.g. darker = higher population density). Best used for: showing spatial patterns of data (unemployment, rainfall, GDP). Limitation: can mislead if areas are very different sizes — a large area with low values looks dominant.\n\n3. Flow Maps (desire lines): show movement — arrows whose width represents the volume of movement (e.g. migration flows, trade routes). Best used for: understanding spatial connections and the direction/scale of movement between places.\n\n4. Dot Maps: each dot represents a set number of occurrences. Best used for: showing where something is concentrated or sparse (e.g. population distribution). Limitation: dots can overlap in dense areas, making patterns hard to read.\n\nThe right map depends on: what you want to show, what your data looks like, and who your audience is.", hint:"For each map type: name it, describe what it shows, say what geographical question it is best suited to answer, and note any limitation." }
    ]},
    { level:2, topic:"Weather & Climate", questions:[
      { id:"g2_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is the key difference between weather and climate?", options:["They are the same thing","Weather is short-term atmospheric conditions; climate is the long-term average pattern","Climate changes daily; weather is permanent","Weather is global; climate is local"], answer:"Weather is short-term atmospheric conditions; climate is the long-term average pattern", hint:"Weather = what it's doing outside TODAY. Climate = what it normally does over 30+ years. 'Climate is what you expect; weather is what you get.'" },
      { id:"g2_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Which factor most influences the UK's mild, wet climate?", options:["Its proximity to the equator","The North Atlantic Drift ocean current and prevailing south-westerly winds","High altitude across the country","The absence of mountains"], answer:"The North Atlantic Drift ocean current and prevailing south-westerly winds", hint:"The UK is warmed by the North Atlantic Drift (an ocean current carrying warm water from the Gulf of Mexico) and by moist south-westerly winds from the Atlantic." },
      { id:"g2_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Explain how a depression (low pressure system) affects UK weather as it passes over.", answer:"A depression brings a warm front then a cold front. Ahead of the warm front: thick cloud, steady rain, falling pressure. Warm sector: mild, drizzly. Cold front: heavy rain, thunderstorms, rapid temperature drop. After: pressure rises, skies clear but cold.", keywords:["depression","warm front","cold front","rain","cloud","pressure"], hint:"Draw the sequence: warm front approaches → warm sector → cold front passes → cold air behind. Each stage has different weather characteristics." },
      { id:"g2_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Describe the main characteristics of a tropical monsoon climate.", answer:"Tropical monsoon climate has high temperatures year-round (25-30°C+). It has a distinct WET season (May-October in South Asia) when the ITCZ moves north bringing heavy convectional rainfall, and a DRY season when the ITCZ moves south. Found in South and South-East Asia, West Africa.", keywords:["monsoon","wet season","dry season","temperature","rainfall","ITCZ"], hint:"Key: distinct wet and dry seasons (not constant rain like equatorial). High temperatures throughout. The ITCZ (Inter-Tropical Convergence Zone) drives the rainfall seasonality." },
      { id:"g2_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Explain the causes and impacts of one extreme weather event in the UK (e.g. flooding, drought, heatwave or severe storm). What short-term and long-term responses were made?", answer:"Choose one UK extreme weather event. Causes = physical (rainfall, pressure systems) + human (land use, climate change). Impacts = social, economic, environmental. Responses = immediate relief + long-term management.", modelAnswer:"Case Study: UK Flooding (e.g. Winter 2015-16, Cumbria — Storm Desmond)\n\nCauses:\n• Physical: intense low-pressure system (Storm Desmond) brought record rainfall — 341mm in 24 hours at Honister Pass (a UK record). Saturated ground from previous wet months meant runoff was almost instant.\n• Human: removal of trees upstream (reducing interception), building on flood plains, climate change increasing intensity of storms\n\nImpacts:\n• Social: 5,000 homes flooded, residents evacuated, mental health effects of displacement\n• Economic: £500 million+ damage to properties, businesses and infrastructure; Carlisle city centre businesses closed for months\n• Environmental: river bank erosion, habitat destruction, water contamination\n\nResponses:\n• Immediate: emergency services, army deployed, temporary flood barriers erected, evacuation of residents\n• Long-term: £3 million raised to repair bridges; plans for new £25m raised flood defences in Carlisle; upstream tree planting schemes (natural flood management)\n\nThis event shows that effective flood management requires both engineering solutions (hard engineering) and working with nature (soft engineering).", hint:"Case study responses score highly if specific. Use real place names, statistics and dates where possible. Structure as: causes → impacts (social/economic/environmental) → responses (immediate/long-term)." }
    ]},
    { level:3, topic:"Rivers & Coasts", questions:[
      { id:"g3_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is hydraulic action?", options:["Rock fragments scraping and wearing away the river bed","The force of water compressing air in cracks, breaking apart rock","Sediment being carried along by river water","Minerals dissolving in river water"], answer:"The force of water compressing air in cracks, breaking apart rock", hint:"Hydraulic action = water POWER. Fast-moving water forces air into cracks in the rock, eventually causing pieces to break off. No tools needed — just force." },
      { id:"g3_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Which landform is typically found at the mouth of a large river?", options:["Meander","Oxbow lake","Delta or estuary","Waterfall"], answer:"Delta or estuary", hint:"At the mouth (where the river meets the sea), flow slows and sediment is deposited. This builds a delta (fan shape) or widens into an estuary." },
      { id:"g3_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Describe the process of longshore drift along a coastline.", answer:"Waves approach the coast at an angle (driven by prevailing winds). The swash carries sediment diagonally up the beach in the direction of the waves. The backwash flows straight back down the beach due to gravity. This zigzag movement transports sediment along the coast in the direction of the prevailing wind.", keywords:["longshore drift","swash","backwash","sediment","angle","prevailing wind"], hint:"Two movements: swash (diagonal, up) and backwash (straight, down). The NET movement of sediment is along the coast. Draw the zigzag if it helps." },
      { id:"g3_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Explain how a waterfall and gorge form, step by step.", answer:"1. A river flows over hard rock overlying softer rock. 2. Soft rock erodes faster (hydraulic action, abrasion). 3. Hard rock is undercut and forms an overhang. 4. Overhang collapses into the plunge pool below. 5. Process repeats, waterfall retreats upstream. 6. A steep-sided gorge is left behind.", keywords:["waterfall","hard rock","soft rock","gorge","erosion","overhang","retreat"], hint:"The waterfall moves BACKWARDS (retreats upstream) over time. The gorge is the valley it leaves behind. Key: hard over soft rock, undercutting, collapse." },
      { id:"g3_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Explain the processes of erosion, transportation and deposition in a river system. Describe one landform created by erosion and one created by deposition.", answer:"Erosion: hydraulic action, abrasion, attrition, solution. Transport: traction, saltation, suspension, solution. Deposition: when energy decreases. Erosion = waterfall/gorge. Deposition = meander/floodplain/delta.", modelAnswer:"River Processes:\n\nEROSION (wearing away material):\n• Hydraulic action: force of water breaks apart the bed and banks\n• Abrasion: rocks carried by river scrape and wear down the bed (sandpaper effect)\n• Attrition: rocks carried by river knock against each other, becoming smaller and rounder\n• Solution: soluble minerals dissolve in slightly acidic river water\n\nTRANSPORTATION (moving material):\n• Traction: large boulders rolled along the river bed\n• Saltation: smaller pebbles bounced along the bed\n• Suspension: fine particles (silt, clay) carried within the water\n• Solution: dissolved minerals carried in water\n\nDEPOSITION: when the river loses energy (slows down) it drops its load. Heaviest material deposited first.\n\nErosion landform — Waterfall and Gorge: formed where hard rock overlies soft rock; soft rock erodes faster, creating an overhang; overhang collapses; waterfall retreats upstream; gorge left behind.\n\nDeposition landform — Floodplain: the wide, flat valley floor either side of a river. During floods, the river bursts its banks and deposits fine, fertile silt across the floodplain. Over time, repeated flooding builds up layers of alluvium, creating flat, fertile agricultural land.", hint:"Four erosion processes (HAAS), four transport processes (TSSS), deposition when energy drops. Name + describe each. For landforms, give the step-by-step formation." }
    ]},
    { level:4, topic:"Population & Migration", questions:[
      { id:"g4_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What does DTM stand for?", options:["Development and Trade Model","Demographic Transition Model","Debt and Trade Measure","Development Threshold Marker"], answer:"Demographic Transition Model", hint:"The DTM describes how birth rates and death rates change as countries develop economically — from high both to low both." },
      { id:"g4_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Which stage of the DTM shows high birth rates and rapidly falling death rates, causing fast population growth?", options:["Stage 1","Stage 2","Stage 3","Stage 4"], answer:"Stage 2", hint:"Stage 2 = early industrial. Death rates fall first (improved medicine, sanitation) but birth rates stay high — so population grows rapidly. Classic in LIC today." },
      { id:"g4_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Distinguish between an economic migrant and a refugee.", answer:"An economic migrant moves voluntarily to seek better work or living conditions — driven by push factors (poverty, unemployment) and pull factors (higher wages, opportunities). A refugee is forced to flee their home country due to persecution, conflict or natural disaster and is protected under international law.", keywords:["economic","refugee","voluntary","persecution","conflict","push","pull","forced"], hint:"The key distinction is CHOICE. Economic migrants choose to move; refugees have no safe choice but to leave." },
      { id:"g4_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Give two causes and two consequences of an ageing population in a developed country (MEDC).", answer:"Causes: falling birth rate (people having fewer children), increasing life expectancy (better healthcare). Consequences: pension/healthcare system under strain (more dependents), shrinking workforce reducing tax revenue, increased demand for social care.", keywords:["ageing","birth rate","life expectancy","pension","healthcare","workforce"], hint:"Causes = WHY there are more old people. Consequences = what that means for society, the economy and public services." },
      { id:"g4_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Evaluate the challenges and opportunities that international migration creates for both the source country and the destination country.", answer:"Source: loses skilled workers (brain drain) but gains remittances. Destination: gains labour and skills but faces pressure on housing and services. Both countries face social and cultural challenges and benefits.", modelAnswer:"International migration creates complex consequences for both countries involved.\n\nFor the SOURCE country:\nChallenges:\n• Brain drain — the most educated and skilled workers leave, reducing the country's economic potential\n• Ageing population — young migrants leave, increasing the dependency ratio\n• Family breakdown — children left behind without parents\n\nOpportunities:\n• Remittances — migrants send money home (global total: >$700 billion/year), directly reducing poverty\n• Returning migrants bring new skills, languages and business experience\n• Reduces unemployment pressure in overcrowded labour markets\n\nFor the DESTINATION country:\nChallenges:\n• Pressure on housing, schools, hospitals — especially in areas of rapid migration\n• Social tension if cultural integration is poorly managed\n• Wages may be suppressed in low-skill sectors\n\nOpportunities:\n• Fills labour shortages (NHS in UK relies heavily on migrant workers)\n• Migrants are often entrepreneurial — creating businesses and jobs\n• Cultural enrichment — food, arts, languages, perspectives\n• Younger migrants pay taxes supporting ageing local populations\n\nOverall, migration is neither simply positive nor negative — its impacts depend on scale, speed, skills profile and the quality of integration policies.", hint:"Structure as: source country (challenges, then opportunities), destination country (challenges, then opportunities). End with a balanced evaluative conclusion." }
    ]},
    { level:5, topic:"Urban Issues", questions:[
      { id:"g5_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is urbanisation?", options:["The growth of rural areas","The process by which an increasing proportion of a country's population lives in urban areas","The decline of city centres","The building of new cities from scratch"], answer:"The process by which an increasing proportion of a country's population lives in urban areas", hint:"Urbanisation = more people living in towns and cities as a proportion of the total population. It's a PROCESS, not just city growth." },
      { id:"g5_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What are informal settlements (shanty towns/squatter settlements) most associated with?", options:["Rural areas in HICs","Rapid urbanisation in LICs and NICs where migrants cannot afford formal housing","Wealthy suburbs of major cities","Government-planned housing districts"], answer:"Rapid urbanisation in LICs and NICs where migrants cannot afford formal housing", hint:"When rural-urban migration is faster than formal housing supply, people self-build on any available land — creating informal settlements. Common in cities like Mumbai, Lagos, Rio de Janeiro." },
      { id:"g5_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Describe two social problems and two environmental problems associated with rapid urbanisation in a low-income country (LIC).", answer:"Social: overcrowding and lack of adequate housing, insufficient schools and hospitals, high crime rates due to poverty and inequality. Environmental: air and water pollution from industry/vehicles/waste, lack of sanitation leading to disease, loss of surrounding farmland/green space.", keywords:["overcrowding","pollution","sanitation","crime","social","environmental","disease"], hint:"Social = problems for PEOPLE (housing, health, safety). Environmental = problems for the ENVIRONMENT (pollution, waste, land use)." },
      { id:"g5_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Explain how urban regeneration can improve quality of life in a city. Use a named example.", answer:"E.g. Manchester's Northern Quarter or London's Canary Wharf/King's Cross: derelict industrial land converted to housing, offices, shops, restaurants; new public transport links; green spaces created. This brings investment, jobs, reduces crime, improves appearance and increases property values.", keywords:["regeneration","housing","employment","transport","quality of life","investment"], hint:"Regeneration = renewing run-down areas. Name a specific place and say what changed (buildings, jobs, transport, crime rates) and how this improved people's lives." },
      { id:"g5_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Evaluate the effectiveness of strategies used to manage urban growth and improve sustainability in a named city in either an LIC/NIC or an HIC.", answer:"Choose one city (e.g. Mumbai, Rio, London, Singapore). Evaluate specific strategies: self-help schemes, site and service, urban planning, transport investment, green initiatives. Assess their success and limitations.", modelAnswer:"Case Study: Rio de Janeiro, Brazil (NIC) — Managing Urban Growth\n\nRio faces extreme urban challenges: 22% of its population (1.5 million people) lives in favelas (informal settlements) — often without clean water, sanitation, legal electricity or formal waste collection.\n\nStrategy 1: Favela Bairro Programme (self-help/site-and-service)\nThe city invested in upgrading existing favelas — adding legal water pipes, sewers, paved roads, electricity and community buildings. Residents added their own improvements. Effectiveness: improved living standards for thousands; gave residents a stake in improvement. Limitation: did not address root causes (inequality, lack of formal employment).\n\nStrategy 2: Cable car (Teleférico) in Complexo do Alemão\nConnected hillside favela to metro network, reducing travel time dramatically for residents. Effectiveness: improved access to jobs and services. Limitation: expensive, and some areas still isolated.\n\nStrategy 3: Pacifying Police Units (UPP)\nPolice reclaimed favelas from drug gangs before 2016 Olympics. Effectiveness: short-term crime reduction. Limitation: crime returned when policing reduced after Olympics — sustainable only with economic development alongside.\n\nOverall evaluation: strategies are more effective when they combine physical infrastructure, social services AND economic opportunity. Piecemeal approaches address symptoms rather than causes.", hint:"Structure: city context (brief), then evaluate 2-3 specific strategies (what it did, how effective, what limitations). End with overall judgement: what made strategies succeed or fail?" }
    ]},
    { level:6, topic:"Economic Development", questions:[
      { id:"g6_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What does the HDI (Human Development Index) measure?", options:["Military strength and trade volume","Life expectancy, education (years of schooling) and income per person","Population growth rate only","GDP only"], answer:"Life expectancy, education (years of schooling) and income per person", hint:"HDI is a composite index: Health (life expectancy) + Education (mean and expected years of schooling) + Income (GNI per capita). Gives a broader picture than GDP alone." },
      { id:"g6_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is a Newly Industrialised Country (NIC)?", options:["A country that has never had any industry","A country that has recently experienced rapid economic growth through industrialisation","A country with the highest GDP in the world","A country entirely dependent on agriculture"], answer:"A country that has recently experienced rapid economic growth through industrialisation", hint:"NICs include countries like China, India, Brazil, Mexico, South Korea — they've moved from mainly agricultural to significant manufacturing/service economies." },
      { id:"g6_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Give two limitations of using GDP per capita as a measure of a country's development.", answer:"1. Does not show how wealth is distributed — a high average hides extreme inequality (e.g. many in poverty despite high GDP). 2. Doesn't measure wellbeing, health or education quality. 3. Doesn't capture informal economy (unregistered activity). 4. Ignores environmental costs of economic activity.", keywords:["GDP","inequality","distribution","wellbeing","limitation","informal"], hint:"GDP tells you HOW MUCH is produced — not WHO benefits, HOW HEALTHY people are, or HOW EDUCATED they are. A rich country can still have widespread poverty." },
      { id:"g6_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Describe Rostow's Stages of Economic Growth model and give one criticism of it.", answer:"Rostow's model (1960) proposed 5 stages all countries pass through: 1. Traditional society 2. Preconditions for take-off 3. Take-off (rapid growth) 4. Drive to maturity 5. Age of high mass consumption. Criticism: based on Western experience; ignores colonialism's role in underdevelopment; assumes one linear path suits all countries.", keywords:["Rostow","stages","take-off","traditional","mass consumption","criticism","linear"], hint:"Rostow said all countries follow the same path. Critics say this ignores how colonialism kept some countries poor and assumes the Western model is universal." },
      { id:"g6_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Evaluate the relative effectiveness of trade versus aid in promoting economic development in lower-income countries (LICs). Use examples to support your argument.", answer:"Trade: sustainable, builds capacity, but LICs face unfair trade rules. Aid: addresses immediate need but can create dependency. Best approach uses both strategically.", modelAnswer:"The debate over trade versus aid has been central to development economics for decades.\n\nTrade as a development tool:\nAdvantages: Trade generates sustainable income, builds industrial capacity, creates employment, and allows countries to specialise. South Korea and China used export-led growth to achieve rapid development.\nLimitations: Trade rules are often unfair to LICs. Rich countries subsidise their own farmers (making LIC agricultural exports uncompetitive). The WTO rules can disadvantage poorer countries. Raw materials often earn less than finished goods — the 'commodity trap'.\n\nAid as a development tool:\nAdvantages: Emergency aid saves lives immediately. Development aid can build infrastructure (schools, hospitals, roads) that trade alone cannot quickly provide. Targeted aid (e.g. vaccines, clean water) has measurable impact.\nLimitations: Aid can create dependency, undermining local production (e.g. free food aid undercuts local farmers). Tied aid (must be spent on donor country goods/services) benefits the donor. Corruption can divert aid from intended recipients.\n\nEvaluation: The most effective development strategies combine both: using aid to build the conditions (infrastructure, education, governance) within which trade can flourish. Countries like Botswana and Rwanda have combined targeted investment with growing export trade successfully. The key is not choosing one over the other but sequencing and integrating them.", hint:"Don't just say trade is better or aid is better — evaluate BOTH with specific advantages and limitations. Use named country examples. End with a nuanced conclusion." }
    ]},
    { level:7, topic:"Natural Hazards", questions:[
      { id:"g7_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What typically occurs at a destructive (convergent) plate boundary where oceanic meets continental crust?", options:["The two plates move apart","The oceanic plate subducts beneath the continental plate","Two continental plates collide head-on","The plates slide horizontally past each other"], answer:"The oceanic plate subducts beneath the continental plate", hint:"Oceanic crust is denser than continental — so it sinks (subducts) beneath continental crust. This creates deep ocean trenches, volcanoes and earthquakes." },
      { id:"g7_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"On the Richter scale, what does each whole number increase represent?", options:["An increase of 10 times the ground shaking amplitude","A doubling of the energy released","An increase of 100 times","An increase of 5 times"], answer:"An increase of 10 times the ground shaking amplitude", hint:"Richter scale is logarithmic. Magnitude 6 = 10× more ground shaking than magnitude 5, and about 31.6× more energy. A magnitude 7 is 100× more shaking than 5." },
      { id:"g7_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Describe two immediate responses and two long-term responses to a major earthquake in an LIC.", answer:"Immediate: search and rescue operations, providing emergency shelter, food and clean water, setting up field hospitals. Long-term: rebuilding infrastructure (roads, homes, schools), improving building codes (earthquake-resistant design), community disaster preparedness training, economic recovery programmes.", keywords:["immediate","long-term","search and rescue","shelter","rebuild","infrastructure","preparedness"], hint:"Immediate = first 72 hours (save lives, meet basic needs). Long-term = weeks, months, years (rebuild, prevent next time)." },
      { id:"g7_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Describe how a tropical storm (hurricane/typhoon/cyclone) forms.", answer:"1. Form over warm ocean water (≥26°C) near the equator. 2. Warm, moist air rises rapidly, creating intense low pressure. 3. As air rises it cools, water vapour condenses releasing latent heat — fuelling further uplift. 4. Air spirals inward due to the Coriolis effect. 5. A calm eye forms at the centre. 6. Storm intensifies over warm water and weakens over land or cooler sea.", keywords:["warm ocean","26°C","low pressure","Coriolis","rotation","moist air","eye"], hint:"Key conditions: warm ocean (energy source), Coriolis effect (causes spinning), low pressure centre. The storm dies when it hits land or cold water — it loses its energy source." },
      { id:"g7_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Compare the impacts of a tectonic hazard (earthquake or volcano) in an HIC with one in an LIC. Explain why the impacts differ.", answer:"HIC: better infrastructure, emergency services, building codes = fewer deaths but high economic cost. LIC: weaker infrastructure, less preparation = far higher death toll relative to population, slower recovery.", modelAnswer:"Case Study Comparison: Haiti Earthquake 2010 (LIC) vs Christchurch Earthquake 2011 (HIC)\n\nHaiti (M7.0, 2010):\n• Deaths: ~230,000 killed\n• 1.5 million people displaced\n• Port-au-Prince largely destroyed — buildings not earthquake resistant\n• Limited emergency services; international aid took days to arrive effectively\n• Recovery: still ongoing 10+ years later; cholera outbreak killed further 10,000\n• Why? Extreme poverty (HDI 0.5), weak governance, poor construction standards, dense informal settlements, limited emergency infrastructure\n\nChristchurch, New Zealand (M6.3, 2011):\n• Deaths: 185 killed\n• Significant building damage — but many buildings had base isolation systems\n• Excellent emergency response within hours\n• Insurance and government compensation allowed rebuilding within 5 years\n• Why? High income (HDI 0.93), strict building codes since 1931 earthquake, well-funded emergency services, effective insurance systems\n\nKey reasons for difference:\n1. Wealth — richer countries can invest in prevention and recovery\n2. Governance — effective institutions coordinate response\n3. Building quality — seismic-resistant buildings save lives\n4. Location — dense informal settlements amplify risk\n5. Social capital — community preparedness and trust in authorities", hint:"Use a specific named example from both an HIC and an LIC. Compare: deaths, economic loss, response time, recovery time. Then explain WHY these differ (wealth, infrastructure, preparation, governance)." }
    ]},
    { level:8, topic:"Resources & Sustainability", questions:[
      { id:"g8_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is water stress?", options:["When a country has no rivers at all","When water demand exceeds reliable supply, or water quality is too poor to use","When water prices are very high","When annual rainfall is below average"], answer:"When water demand exceeds reliable supply, or water quality is too poor to use", hint:"Water stress occurs when a country withdraws more than 25% of its renewable freshwater resources annually, or when water quality makes available water unusable." },
      { id:"g8_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What does food security mean?", options:["Keeping food refrigerated and fresh","All people at all times having physical, social and economic access to sufficient, safe and nutritious food","Preventing theft of food supplies","Government control over food production"], answer:"All people at all times having physical, social and economic access to sufficient, safe and nutritious food", hint:"Food security has three pillars: availability (food exists), access (people can get it), utilisation (it is nutritious and safe). All three must be met." },
      { id:"g8_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Give two causes of water insecurity in LICs and explain each.", answer:"1. Rapid population growth increases demand faster than infrastructure can expand supply. 2. Lack of water treatment and distribution infrastructure means available water is contaminated or unreachable. Also: climate change reducing reliable rainfall; pollution of water sources by industry or agriculture; inability to afford desalination or purification technology.", keywords:["population","infrastructure","climate","demand","contamination","pollution"], hint:"Think about supply AND demand. Water insecurity can come from too little water (drought, geography) or from water that exists but cannot be used safely or distributed." },
      { id:"g8_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Explain how an energy mix strategy can improve a country's energy security.", answer:"Energy security = reliable, affordable access to energy. Diversifying the energy mix (combining renewables, nuclear and conventional sources) reduces dependence on imported fossil fuels, insulates against price shocks, and ensures supply if one source fails. Renewables provide long-term domestic generation; nuclear provides reliable baseload; domestic fossil fuels reduce import dependency.", keywords:["energy mix","renewable","security","diversify","imports","nuclear","domestic"], hint:"Energy security is about not being too dependent on any ONE source or supplier. Diversification = don't put all your eggs in one basket." },
      { id:"g8_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Evaluate the role of technology in addressing global food insecurity. Refer to specific examples of technology and assess both their potential and their limitations.", answer:"Technologies: GM crops, precision farming, irrigation efficiency, vertical farming, lab-grown meat. Each has potential but faces limitations (cost, access, cultural resistance, ecological risk).", modelAnswer:"Technology offers significant potential to address food insecurity, but its effectiveness depends on whether it reaches those who need it most.\n\nGM (Genetically Modified) Crops:\nPotential: Golden Rice contains Vitamin A precursor — could address malnutrition in South and South-East Asia. Drought-resistant and pest-resistant GM varieties could maintain yields in changing climates.\nLimitations: Patent control by agribusiness means seeds are expensive; farmers cannot save seed. Public resistance in many countries (EU restrictions). Potential ecological risks (gene transfer to wild species) are contested.\n\nPrecision Agriculture (GPS-guided irrigation, drone monitoring, AI analysis):\nPotential: reduces water use by 30-50%, optimises fertiliser application, monitors crop health — reducing waste and increasing yields.\nLimitations: requires expensive technology and reliable internet. Not accessible to smallholder farmers in LICs who produce much of the world's food.\n\nVertical Farming:\nPotential: produces food in urban areas with minimal land and water use; year-round production independent of climate.\nLimitations: high energy costs (artificial lighting), very high set-up costs, currently limited to high-value salad crops.\n\nOverall evaluation: Technology can improve food production, but food insecurity is fundamentally a problem of distribution and poverty, not just production. The world already produces enough food calories for everyone. Technology that increases yield but remains inaccessible to LIC farmers does not address the root causes of food insecurity.", hint:"For each technology: name it, explain its potential to address food insecurity, then critically assess its limitations. End with a conclusion that goes beyond the technology itself." }
    ]},
    { level:9, topic:"Ecosystems & Biomes", questions:[
      { id:"g9_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is a biome?", options:["A single plant species","A large-scale global ecosystem characterised by its climate and dominant vegetation type","A small pond ecosystem","A type of rock formation"], answer:"A large-scale global ecosystem characterised by its climate and dominant vegetation type", hint:"Biomes are large global zones: tropical rainforest, savanna, desert, temperate forest, taiga, tundra, etc. Each is defined by climate and the plants/animals adapted to it." },
      { id:"g9_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Where are tropical rainforests primarily found?", options:["At the poles (60-90° latitude)","Between the tropics of Cancer and Capricorn, near the equator (0-23°N/S)","Across central Europe and North America","In hot desert regions"], answer:"Between the tropics of Cancer and Capricorn, near the equator (0-23°N/S)", hint:"Rainforests need consistently high temperatures and rainfall — conditions found near the equator. Major areas: Amazon Basin, Congo Basin, South-East Asia." },
      { id:"g9_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Describe three ways in which tropical rainforest plants are adapted to their environment.", answer:"1. Drip tips on leaves allow heavy rainfall to run off quickly, preventing disease and fungal growth. 2. Buttress roots provide stability in thin, nutrient-poor soil and spread widely to capture surface nutrients. 3. Smooth bark on tall trees allows rapid water drainage. 4. Epiphytes (e.g. orchids) grow on branches to access sunlight in the canopy. 5. Lianas (woody vines) climb from dark forest floor to light.", keywords:["drip tips","buttress roots","canopy","adapted","epiphytes","sunlight","nutrient"], hint:"Think about the challenges of the rainforest: too much rain, poor soil, competition for light. Each adaptation solves one of these problems." },
      { id:"g9_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Explain how deforestation of the Amazon rainforest threatens biodiversity and contributes to climate change.", answer:"Amazon contains ~10% of all Earth's species — deforestation destroys habitats, driving extinction. Trees store carbon; felling releases CO₂. Roots hold soil; deforestation causes erosion and soil degradation. Trees release water vapour; deforestation disrupts regional rainfall patterns. Creates positive feedback loops accelerating both biodiversity loss and climate change.", keywords:["deforestation","biodiversity","carbon","habitat","CO₂","climate","extinction","rainfall"], hint:"Two main themes: BIODIVERSITY (species loss through habitat destruction) and CLIMATE (carbon storage lost, rainfall patterns disrupted). Show how they are linked." },
      { id:"g9_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Evaluate the value of tropical rainforests to people and the planet. Assess the effectiveness of strategies used to protect them.", answer:"Value: biodiversity, medicines, carbon storage, indigenous peoples, climate regulation, water cycle. Strategies: national parks, REDD+, debt-for-nature swaps, sustainable logging. Each has strengths and limitations.", modelAnswer:"Value of Tropical Rainforests:\n\nEcological value:\n• Biodiversity: rainforests cover ~6% of Earth's land but contain over 50% of its species — an irreplaceable genetic library\n• Carbon sinks: the Amazon stores ~150 billion tonnes of carbon; its destruction would dramatically accelerate climate change\n• Water cycle: trees transpire huge volumes of water, generating 'flying rivers' of moisture that bring rainfall to distant regions (e.g. the Cerrado, Brazil's agricultural heartland)\n\nHuman value:\n• 25% of modern medicines derive from rainforest plants; only ~1% of species have been scientifically studied\n• ~1 million indigenous people depend on the Amazon for food, medicine and culture\n• Ecotourism provides income without destruction\n\nProtection Strategies:\n\n1. National Parks and Protected Areas: Banning logging/farming in designated zones. Effective where enforcement is strong (e.g. Costa Rica). Limitation: weak enforcement in remote areas; does not address poverty driving deforestation.\n\n2. REDD+ (Reducing Emissions from Deforestation and Degradation): Pays LIC governments to protect forests. Provides financial incentive to keep forests standing. Limitation: complex to implement; difficult to verify; corruption risks.\n\n3. Sustainable logging/FSC certification: Allows selective logging with replanting. Limitation: 'sustainable' standards vary; certification can be bought; enforcement difficult.\n\nOverall: protection works best when it combines economic alternatives for local people, strong governance, international funding, and indigenous land rights — not just restrictions.", hint:"Structure: value (ecological + human) then strategies (name each, assess effectiveness, identify limitations). Conclude with what combination of approaches is most effective." }
    ]},
    { level:10, topic:"Fieldwork & Exam Mastery", questions:[
      { id:"g10_1", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"What is a transect in geographical fieldwork?", options:["A circular survey area","A straight line along which measurements or observations are taken at regular intervals","A type of graph used to display results","A structured questionnaire"], answer:"A straight line along which measurements or observations are taken at regular intervals", hint:"A transect captures how something changes across a distance — e.g. vegetation changes from beach to sand dunes, or traffic changes from town centre outward." },
      { id:"g10_2", marks:1, type:"mcq", q:"Which sampling method gives every member of a population an equal chance of being selected?", options:["Systematic sampling","Stratified sampling","Random sampling","Opportunistic sampling"], answer:"Random sampling", hint:"Random = every element has an equal probability of selection (e.g. using random number tables). Systematic = every nth item. Stratified = proportional from subgroups. Opportunistic = whatever is convenient (least reliable)." },
      { id:"g10_3", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Explain three ways you could assess the reliability of primary data collected during geographical fieldwork.", answer:"1. Repeat measurements at the same location — if results are consistent, they are reliable. 2. Use a large enough sample size to reduce the effect of anomalies. 3. Compare primary data with secondary sources (maps, statistics) — agreement increases confidence. 4. Check for and investigate anomalous results. 5. Use multiple methods to measure the same variable.", keywords:["repeat","sample size","anomalies","reliable","secondary data","comparison","consistent"], hint:"Reliability = can you trust the results? Check by: repeating, comparing, using large samples, investigating outliers." },
      { id:"g10_4", marks:3, type:"short", q:"Which type of graph or map is most suitable for displaying each of the following: (a) change in river width downstream, (b) proportion of land uses in a city, (c) the distribution of earthquakes worldwide?", answer:"(a) Line graph — shows change over distance/time. (b) Pie chart or divided bar chart — shows proportions of a whole. (c) Dot map or choropleth map — shows spatial distribution of events.", keywords:["line graph","pie chart","dot map","choropleth","bar chart","distribution","proportion"], hint:"Match the data type to the graph: CHANGE over time/distance → line graph. PROPORTIONS → pie chart. SPATIAL DISTRIBUTION → map. COMPARING categories → bar chart." },
      { id:"g10_5", marks:5, type:"extended", q:"Design a geographical investigation to study the impact of distance from a town centre on the quality of the urban environment. Justify your choice of methods, explain how you would ensure the data is reliable, and discuss the limitations of your approach.", answer:"Use: environmental quality surveys along transects, pedestrian counts, land use mapping, questionnaires. Justify each. Reliability: repeats, large samples, standardised forms. Limitations: subjectivity, single day, weather effects.", modelAnswer:"Title: How does environmental quality change with distance from the town centre?\n\nHypothesis: Environmental quality will improve with distance from the town centre as land use shifts from commercial to residential.\n\nData Collection Methods:\n\n1. Environmental Quality Survey (EQS): A standardised scoring sheet rating 8-10 criteria (litter, noise, condition of buildings, green space, pedestrian safety) on a scale of 1-5 at regular intervals (every 200m) along a transect from the town centre outward. Justification: provides comparable, quantifiable data across locations. Limitation: subjective — different surveyors may score differently. Solution: use same surveyor throughout, or average multiple surveyors' scores.\n\n2. Pedestrian/Traffic Count: Count people and vehicles passing a fixed point for 5 minutes at each location. Justification: measures activity level, which correlates with commercial intensity. Limitation: varies by time of day — conduct all counts at the same time.\n\n3. Land Use Mapping: Record land use type (retail, residential, industrial, open space) at each survey point. Justification: provides objective context for EQS scores.\n\nEnsuring Reliability:\n• Repeat measurements at each point (3 times, calculate mean)\n• Survey on same day type (weekday vs weekend matters)\n• Use standardised forms\n• Collect data in groups to cross-check scores\n• Large enough sample: at least 8-10 survey points\n\nLimitations:\n• Single-day survey may not represent typical conditions\n• Sample points may not capture all variation\n• EQS remains subjective despite standardisation\n• Cannot control for special events (markets, roadworks)", hint:"Structure as a formal investigation plan: title/hypothesis, methods (justify each one), reliability measures, limitations. Show you can think critically about your own methodology — this is what top marks require." }
    ]}
  ]}
};
